commit_message:
Don't delete DVR namespace if there are still ports on this node

Skip deleting DVR namespaces if they contain ports in the BUILD or
DOWN status.

Change-Id: I026f2014ede800c0f4532ca15f1fccdaa59d5b61
Closes-bug: #1464527

commit_message:
Restricts pipeline to have unique source names

Sample and event pipelines are validated for unique
sink names and unique pipeline names(combined source
and sink names), but not unique source names.

This fix validates source names to be unique in
pipeline.

Also refactors the logic to validate sink and pipe
names for duplicates using set instead of list
iteration.

Change-Id: I349b48fc5e50f1bb16e453a0052021b855230ccc
Closes-Bug: 1466136

commit_message:
Minor doc fixups in ansible-deployment.md

* Capitalise all usages of "Ansible", "Kolla", and "OpenStack"

* Add note to let users know ssh key setup is not necessary for the aio
  demo.

* Add note to remind users to update the koalla_directory variable.

Change-Id: Icb5c1237aa5de049445cb417e565da550dc87daf

commit_message:
Fix Heat container env vars and dependencies

This commit adds a few dependencies (that are actually packaging errors)
present in all of the containers, as well as specifically in
heat-engine. Some of the environment variables were not set correctly in
the heat-api-cfn container. The environment variables have also been
correctly added to the genenv script.

Also removed duplicated compose file data already present in
heat-api-engine.

Closes-Bug: #1461872
Change-Id: I9631d1bc6ea42425272570a9dda8cbf5edcef4f3

commit_message:
Use cloned novaclient for functional testing

Previously used novaclient modification (v14 of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/152569/) is too obsolete. It is not
compatible with modern oslo libraries. Current version of this
modification (v34) is obsolete as well.

The proposed solution is to use a separate novaclient repository, which
can be maintained independently of community. Until microversions are
not supported by novaclient upstream.

Depends-On: I75e1bbcd81678a56a0940b696cfa5dbc2c159cc6
Change-Id: I3c84e5f97ce41af2215660ef80c74e2fd8334d3c

commit_message:
Merge disk-config func test between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges disk-config functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.
Also enabling some required extension for v2 tests.

Change-Id: Ic13d5e67ec992936e3899904b8a7ec7e4488716f

commit_message:
Dedicate aggregates for specific tenants

Extend the "AggregateMultiTenancyIsolation" scheduler filter
in order to optionally exclude instances frombeing scheduled
for deployment in hosts that don't belong to the defined
aggregate(s). This behavior is enforced by operator for
all users.

blueprint multi-tenancy-isolation-only-aggregates

Change-Id: I57428ef713386a8882ab19b0ac42648e7acde155
Co-Authored-By: Michal Rostecki <michal.rostecki@allegrogroup.com>

[{'created': '2015-05-10 14:55:40.000000000', 'message': "Fix LIO target helper when missing targetcli

After patch to fix LIO target persistence was merged a bug was
introduced where target creation/removal would result in an exception if
targetcli is not installed on the system.

This patch fixes this by checking if patch to the default file exists on
the system and creating it if doesn't.

Change-Id: I5ecc1ae47482ea43a4890ccd81a4e872ab570069
Closes-Bug: #1453518

commit_message:
Fix LIO target helper when missing targetcli

After patch to fix LIO target persistence was merged, a bug was
introduced where target creation/removal would result in an exception if
targetcli is not installed on the system.

This patch fixes this by checking if path to the default file exists on
the system and creating it if doesn't.

Change-Id: I5ecc1ae47482ea43a4890ccd81a4e872ab570069
Closes-Bug: #1453518

commit_message:
Fix the description in tempest.conf.sample

Ic2e5bd127c9f3a0f2807a25f29d8693baf3d65f2 of oslo.log has changed
the description of use_syslog, but current tempest.conf.sample does
not contain this change. As the result, the pep8 test continuously
fails on the gate now.
This patch fixes this description.

In addition, this patch adds fake body message to NotFound in
javelin test for avoiding the gate problem.

These gate problems happened at the same time, so this patch contains
mutiple purposes but that is necessary for fixing at the same time.

Closes-Bug: #1468141
Closes-Bug: #1468149
Change-Id: Iada215718651dc153b977008b376a956247ebc5d

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-22 15:48:32.000000000', 'message': "Ease debugging alembic by passing proper scripts path in alembic.ini

Otherwise, anyone who attempts to issue an alembic command with the file
gets:

  FAILED: Path doesn't exist:
  '<...>/neutron/neutron/db/migration/alembic'.  Please use the 'init'
  command to create a new scripts folder.

Change-Id: I5b5f2802b478c8d8c327d24faa838f7a6859b979
"}]
commit_message:
Ease debugging alembic by passing proper scripts path in alembic.ini

Otherwise, anyone who attempts to issue an alembic command with the file
gets:

  FAILED: Path doesn't exist:
  '<...>/neutron/neutron/db/migration/alembic'.  Please use the 'init'
  command to create a new scripts folder.

Change-Id: I5b5f2802b478c8d8c327d24faa838f7a6859b979

Error message for invalid cluster details page

Using an invalid cluster ID for cluster details URL causes a stack trace.
This patch adds a proper error message for this case.

Closes-Bug: #1463838

commit_message:
Fix testing object fields with missing instance rows

This test was not actually always triggering the exception in the right
place because the is-set condition was not being forced true, even though
the is-changed one was.

This just mocks out the is-set check to make it look like it is always
set, which makes sure we actually run this for each case properly. It
also resets changes to make sure that we end up with a clean instance
each time through the loop.

This avoids failures later when we drop some flavor compat stuff.

Also, this moves the test to the local-only test class for reasons
mentioned in the comments.

Closes-Bug: #1468087

Change-Id: I4cb6169119da1074c823f3319294ba880a67758f

commit_message:
Make resp_body optional on RestClientException

The commit Ie1bb259e7e683081f0ad127617acc8deb98467c0 adds resp_body
to RestClientException, but it broke some unit tests of Tempest
because NotFound calls don't pass the resp_body.
So the above commit was backwards incompatible changes, this patch
makes resp_body optional for avoiding affecting to the other projects.

Change-Id: Ic75f0673f27fb23c2784f2f8dbceab70061d3823

commit_message:
Optimize getting unit in "metering" dashboard

Currently we using a meter-list for getting a "unit" for metric.
Meter list get all available metric on environment,
it's may be a thousands of records.
It's better to use sample-list for this metric with "limit" 1.
This request gets a 1 sample for queried metric.

Change-Id: I4bf0ab7ebcbcae1ddc90d8ee01d5f5a84ed4fbba
Related-bug: #1444456

commit_message:
Remove redundant python-pip package install

Since we already bootstrap pip, and upgrade it, this removes
redundant packages which appear to be causing the bifrost
gate job to fail.

Change-Id: If96f0a8705bfd5039bf9661e26f5b230875a1477
Closes-Bug: 1468158

commit_message:
Add missing tenant_id to lbaas-v2 resources creation

Now tenant_id is not specific when creating lbaas v2 loadbalancer, listener,
pool, member. This patch add missing tenant_id to lbaas-v2 resources
creation. So admin user can create resource for specific project.

Closes-Bug: #1453706
(cherry picked from commit d5360202e16b635eac907fe1f30bf387b39e238d)

Change-Id: I57a668f6fe0f793cfae1b4db5134e4d0b6f0c0c8

[{'created': '2015-05-11 08:15:58.000000000', 'message': 'Add missing tenant_id to lbaas-v2 resources creation

Now tenant_id is not specific when creating lbaas v2 loadbalancer, listener,
pool, member. This patch add missing tenant_id to lbaas-v2 resources
creation. So admin user can create resource for specific project.

Change-Id: If4db4d8660354bc1f4d5259ebed73d78b4cfcd97
Closes-Bug: #1453706
'}]
commit_message:
Add missing tenant_id to lbaas-v2 resources creation

Now tenant_id is not specific when creating lbaas v2 loadbalancer, listener,
pool, member. This patch add missing tenant_id to lbaas-v2 resources
creation. So admin user can create resource for specific project.

Change-Id: If4db4d8660354bc1f4d5259ebed73d78b4cfcd97
Closes-Bug: #1453706

[{'created': '2015-06-22 13:15:26.000000000', 'message': 'Remove unnecessary wrapping of transformer ExtentionManager

Currently, the TransformerExtensionManager is used to wrap the
ExtentionManager of stevedore.extension just to provide getting extension
by name functionality, this is naturally supported by stevedore. This
change remove the unnecessary code.

Change-Id: I0b7bfa40e4131236b4adedc8b4bdcd70c14d5680
'}]
commit_message:
Remove unnecessary wrapping of transformer ExtentionManager

Currently, the TransformerExtensionManager is used to wrap the
ExtentionManager of stevedore.extension just to provide getting extension
by name functionality, this is naturally supported by stevedore. This
change remove the unnecessary code.

Change-Id: I0b7bfa40e4131236b4adedc8b4bdcd70c14d5680

commit_message:
Normalizing Karma configuration

This cleans up the karma configuration to use auto-discovery
in place of explicitly listing files.

Change-Id: I7b05f7d6921af3a577270638a02717d04e7b20cd
Closes-Bug: #1467684

commit_message:
Fix the setup_workspace to handle missing ZUUL_BRANCH

This commit adds logic to the setup_workspace function to be able to
handle the case where the var ZUUL_BRANCH isn't set. This is what
apparently happens during periodic jobs and causes those to fail.
If ZUUL_BRANCH isn't set we just use the fallback zuul ref which is
what the expected behavior would be if the function didn't explode.

Change-Id: I77b98b8a8d8602da0092a5250cc0ce49de9215db

commit_message:
Python 3: Use range instead of xrange for py3 compatibility.

The function `xrange` was renamed to `range` in Python 3.
xrange is no longer available in py3, thus replacing xrange
with range.
Change-Id: I27ebf620eff3ced286bea3a96c5c1bab3edbc796

commit_message:
Make db-manage script use same config file as barbican

Instead of having to specify the db-url every time we need to do a
migration, this CR enables the db-manage script to use the same config
file as barbican.

Change-Id: I2dd74b6af285119bfb7155925dbf6aa33d55bc46

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-04 20:26:11.000000000', 'message': "Use correct endpoint scheme for api to registry connection

The ['openstack']['image']['ssl']['enabled'] was being used for
both the API service AND it's connection to the registry. Need
to allow for folks that was the API service to be SSL, but the
internal connection to the registry non-ssl.   Using the registry
internal endpoint scheme (http or https) works perfectly for this
task.

Change-Id: Ieed28ad891192d81356c0d40ba48d70517087950
Closes-Bug: #1459169
"}, {'created': '2015-06-05 14:59:02.000000000', 'message': "Use correct endpoint scheme for api to registry connection

The ['openstack']['image']['ssl']['enabled'] was being used for
both the API/Regsitry services AND the APIs internal connection
to the registry.

Need to allow for separate control for enabling SSL for API and Registry.
Added attributes to cover this.

And the APIs internal connection to the registry needs to be
configured correctly based upon the Registry's internal endpoint scheme
(http or https).

Change-Id: Ieed28ad891192d81356c0d40ba48d70517087950
Closes-Bug: #1462388

commit_message:
Use correct endpoint scheme for api to registry connection

The ['openstack']['image']['ssl']['enabled'] was being used for
both the API/Regsitry services AND the APIs internal connection
to the registry.

Need to allow for separate control for enabling SSL for API and Registry.
Added attributes to cover this.

And the APIs internal connection to the registry needs to be
configured correctly based upon the Registry's internal endpoint scheme
(http or https).

Change-Id: Ieed28ad891192d81356c0d40ba48d70517087950
Closes-Bug: #1462388

commit_message:
DB: Support filter_by status in get_bay_list

bay list filter doesn't support filter_by status currently
this is useful if we want to pull bay status in [status1, statu2].

This patch add status(which is a list) filter when query from db.

Closes-Bug: #1467853
Change-Id: Id6d0618b8030883b1a534d2f27dda4c6464eb0a1

commit_message:
Allow keystone under apache

Keystone is recommended to run under apache and the service side
is already deprecated and will be removed in the M release.
This patch adds a new recipe, server-apache, to allow keystone
under apache.

I intentionally just copied the existing server recipe and spec to
create the new ones and I figure those will just be removed in
the M release anyway, no need for "common" type code here.

The majority of the recipe code is exactly the same, just the
last lines, "Start of Apache..." have been added.

This should also work with the existing dashboard cookbook with the
one exception that the apache 3.1 cookbook is needed.  There's already
a patch out for that.

I don't plan on changing the default kilo role to use this, that will
be done once we branch for liberty.

Change-Id: I1641e1e5c6bf56d0765ef6e54ae32848431f6d6e
Implements: blueprint keystone-apache

commit_message:
Unknown type 'any' in pythonk8sclient removed.

Currently the generated code has type 'any' in many models which leads to
error 'ImportError'. So this patch removes all 'any' type to relevant types
of the attributes.

Change-Id: I333b1edd2c84875c48db1e5ff2655360ffcc9718
Closes-bug: #1467345

commit_message:
Show not-in-global errors again.

This regressed when I half-split it into actions and IO (exception
raising). Moving it entirely into actions lets us see all the errors
very easily.

Change-Id: I12e6d910bf983841b4ad81aa41a95bf341456fe4

and battle tested.

commit_message:
Add upper-constraints.txt.

This is a first approximation to the transitive union of requirements,
built by generate-constraints with python 2.7 and 3.4. It will be
updated by a periodic job (which we'll add shortly) proposing future
merges to this repository. Its not yet cross-checked for compatibility
with proposed global-requirements.txt changes, that will come later.

Having the file present now allows us to start working on the
consuming side in parallel and has no downsides, since no projects
jobs will be voting based on this until all the pieces are in place
and battle tested.

Change-Id: Ifc04c81fd8d52051a0f09a6fd61b06da035c513f

commit_message:
Remove icehouse compat jobs from tempest

This commit removes the icehouse compat jobs from the tempest queues.
The icehouse branch will be eol'd at the end of this week, the final
release has already been pushed. However, a recent oslo release has
broken all of the icehouse jobs. Since the release is no longer
supported let's just remove the jobs to unblock tempest.

Change-Id: Ie0cec835c250cd9180e3083ae2d3c28dff78e3fc

commit_message:
Teach the constraints generator about excludes.

Some things like flake8 can't be constrained, so we need an opt-out
clause.

Change-Id: I11eb0d762869ad8920795fb710f1b2eeb9354f12

commit_message:
Object: pass filter to bay list

get_bay_list in db api layer has support adding filters before query bay,
but bay object doesn't pass filter yet.

This patch enables filter by adding parameter filter in bay's list method.

Closes-Bug: #1467735
Change-Id: I7969727544dff2c4bf5e556ccac1c5574a8f6620

commit_message:
Wait until the image is registered in Sahara image test

The tests consistently fails, probably because the availability
of the image in the table is checked too soon. Add a bit of delay
with a new wait method.

Change-Id: I9e39c35fb67455b4e4f3c2b12265b8540420ad01
Closes-Bug: #1466744

commit_message:
Bump minimum requirement for os-client-config

There is a new API in os-client-config 1.4.0 that is needed to add
more complete os-client-config support to openstacksdk.

Change-Id: I23144c597e9c184b1155a29b559d610e43dc913b

commit_message:
Fix typo in container controller

image_id is not used for baymodel, just used for container.
This commit fixes it.

Change-Id: Id8a9fa95698d6b73d02b2687803f9614e612842d
Closes-Bug: #1465558

share server where the snapshot is placed.

commit_message:
Allow drivers to ask for additional share_servers

Add new method choose_share_server_compatible_for_share()
to Share Driver interface. This method is executed in
Share Manager on share creation step to filter existing
share servers. Driver should choose one share server from
the list or return None. If this method returns None, then
Share Manager starts the creation of new share server.

Also, this commit adds a possibility to create share
from a snapshot on share server which differs from original
share server where the snapshot is placed.

Implements bp allow-additional-share-servers

Change-Id: Ia85fcf69b953c199808d7e7d3cb0652c2425fd9d

commit_message:
Angular translation makemessages for singular An approach to i18n for Angular HTML templates. This patch allow only singular translation. Plural and context will be address in subsequent patches. Steps to verify that it works: 1. Create a new html file in horizon/static or openstack_dashboard/static 2. Add something like
hello world!
to the html 3. Run ./run_test.sh --makemessages 4. Inspect your djangojs.po file, it should be there. 5. Run ./run_test.sh --pseudo de 6. Run ./run_test.sh --compilemessages 7. Go to http://localhost:9000/settings 8. Change Language to Deutsch 9. Go to http://localhost:9000/i18n/js/horizon+openstack_dashboard 10. Your translated text should be there as well. Change-Id: I4f417e16ccd0b11b3a1923578e4c7156da2ce10f Partially-Implements: blueprint angular-translate-makemessages

commit_message:
Mark as Python2.7 only the dependencies that are.

We shouldn't try to install on 3.x dependencies that are only
supported on < 3.0. I've used =='2.7' rather than <'3.0' because
setuptools support for < is still spotty and we're tracking that down
and we don't support 2.6 anymore AIUI. I can make this an OR clause
with both 2.6 and 2.7 if we still care about 2.6.

Change-Id: I03667e3e76fd8d84b75dcb5b61742a3f13040662
Depends-On: I2c4cb4305fec81a5fd237edabee78874ccd0da22

commit_message:
Only install python-libguestfs bindings when needed

Currently those bindings are missing from SLES12, and since
they're not actually used unless file injection is enabled
(which is not by default), only conditionally depend on it.

Change-Id: I79a8d8ac7ad2fbd7d2fce696821d130218e43e03

commit_message:
Fix Cinder Objects unit tests

Due to the import order all tests passed on CI. But you can not
run cinder.unit.objects.test_backup only. This patch fixes it
adding base class and invokes objects.register_all().

Change-Id: If6168bce88489840b5d25b97be1f285737d943df

commit_message:
Rebase: move nova VNC conf opts to 'vnc' group

The following Nova change set moved VNC-related config options to a
'vnc' group.

commit 380c4d750f8c53c8ab862082984079a633043b9c
Author: Diana Clarke <diana.joan.clarke@gmail.com>
Date:   Sun Jun 21 23:13:26 2015 -0400

    Register the vnc config options under group 'vnc'

    Also renamed 'vnc_enabled' to 'enabled', and 'vnc_keymap' to
'keymap' now
    that those options are prefixed by the 'vnc' group.

    Change-Id: I2ff668d4ebd8e6ebf9bf4e8ca5b077958f051144
    Closes-Bug: #1447528

Rebase to accomodate the change.

Change-Id: I455275feb7b71e156b8b68f906efb1ffa7cbb548

commit_message:
drop use of oslo.db private attribute

new oslo.db is deprecating existing EngineFacade. a private attr
was removed which our code incorrectly uses. it is not necessary
to use it anyways.

initially introduced here: I57b6d89f30c065643dbfab958e032f2adac59cd6
Closes-Bug: #1468082

Change-Id: I5bc9c3d144294749bee28f5ea78e93861c24bc29

commit_message:
Fix for multiple entries in ucast_mac_remote

checking mac and logical switch while creating l2-gateway-connection,
if there is entry in ucast_mac_remote for second l2-gateway-connection for
same logical switch.
taken care of deleting ucast_mac_remote and vlan_bindings
while deleting l2-gateway-connection.

Closes-Bug:1447910

Co-Authored-By: Phani Pawan <ppawan@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: MANJUNATH PATIL <mpatil@hp.com>

Change-Id: Id9205c902210d94d7168eb95fbd6c3520fbb6239

commit_message:
Fix for internal server error

internal server error occurs if empty l2gateway is passed in
_check_port_fault_status_and_switch_fault_status.so checking the the same.

Closes-Bug: 1454670

commit_message:
Add base image for oraclelinux

This patch provides the basis for an alternate set of images to be
available in Kolla, based on oraclelinux.

It is difficult ahead of time to know all base dependencies and exactly
which repos they'll come from, so at this time I have just added the bare
minimum.

In the next commit keystone will require some essentials that will
likely make sense to add here.

NOTE: To build this image you must set the following .buildconf in the
root of the kolla repo:

cat >> .buildconf << EOF
PREFIX=ol-binary-
EOF

Partially implements: blueprint add-optional-oraclelinux-images

Change-Id: I1ccce8eebe8fa0d4342af2aa482c083d074bda66

commit_message:
Possible parallel version.

Use with caution: its possible db locks will defeat the parallelism
this attempts and make everything slower, not faster. If so, rewriting
it to use one thread per context instead of just plain parallelism
should work.

Change-Id: I5d810941feb0c49fb6323270b855c06da07f3bc7

commit_message:
SUSE: Clean up libxslt/libxml2 related dependencies

libxml2-devel is a dependency of libxslt-devel, so we don't need
to explicitly include it. Also, since it is only really needed
by python-lxml, consolidate it into devlibs and remove the copies.
Also remove a non-existing package reference along the way

Change-Id: If9afaaa93f2c485baa1efff74d7ae58c59713de6

commit_message:
Make resize api of compute manager to send flavor object

This code change implements the conversion of flavor to use object. Rpcapi of
compute manager sends objects for new version and sents primitivized data for
older versions.

Related to blueprint liberty-objects

Change-Id: I11a28cd3b2eb98b42d78f9327ed6b38dc2bc8f30

commit_message:
Add yaql

yaql is actively used by two openstack projects - Murano and Mistral.
Heat community also considered using yaql for imperative things in
Heat templates.

Information about project:
* Hosted on stackforge
* Uses standard tools such as tox, pbr, testrepository
* Python3 compatible
* It is packaged in Debian: https://tracker.debian.org/pkg/python-yaql

Adding yaql to global-requirements will help Murano and Mistral to
adopt Infra automation for automated update of requirements (Proposal Bot).
It also might help adoption of yaql in other projects.

Change-Id: I1881bccc988033b4ee8b587b233010c2d224a93e

commit_message:
mariadb-app missing symlink

The mariadb-app container wouldn't build because it was missing
a symbolic link to mysql-entrypoint.sh.  This was causing the
gate to fail entirely.

Change-Id: I5fc4db2a8c92403ee9d3f41dbdd2a156227a2aa3
Closes-bug: #1467280

commit_message:
Add convenience tox environments

Add a venv tox environment like we use in other projects to build a
virtualenv and run commands.

Add an 'update' environment to run the command for updating the
requirements in another project.

Add a 'generate' environment to run the command for generating
constraints.

Change-Id: Ib99fb4da6f62afd31339fa698c8f0e50ce817128

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-12 15:00:40.000000000', 'message': 'Ansible playbooks and roles to deploy OpenStack

Request to add the os-ansible-deployment project to OpenStack namespace.
os-ansible-deployment (OSAD) is a project dedicated to deploying OpenStack
clouds using Ansible and upstream OpenStack source code without the addition
of vendor driven packaging.

This project is already using all of the OpenStack infrastructure and services
and is gated through gerrit with testing being done on the whole stack using
tempest on our three supported branches.

We are committed to furthering our mission of a great
developer/deployer/operator experience and intend to build out the system to
support all of the OpenStack named services.

We use the OpenStack dev/operators mailing list (albeit unfrequently) and hold
meetings twice weekly[1] (one in our channel and the other in an official
OpenStack meeting channel which is logged[2]).

The IRC channel #openstack-ansible is logged[3], and active with community
members, core developers and like minted people all helping and discusing issues
within the project as well as questions that come us from using Ansible to
operate and manage clouds.

The scope of os-ansible-deployment is to provide tooling for deploying OpenStack
using ansible which will include contributing to the efforts of upstream
Ansible. We are already working with the community to ensure that our efforts
are not duplicated or being made in direct contrast to what upstream Ansible is
already providing. While we do have some overlap within our currectly carried
modules, the OpenStack client modules we have in tree, we are commited to moving
that functionality and code into upstream just as we've done with our other
plugins/modules[4][5].

With this projects move to "big tent" we'd only be looking to bring with us the
Master and Kilo branches as they've been designed to be community code with
all of the original Rackspace-isms removed. This would mean that the Juno and
Icehouse branches would be left behind in StackForge as they'd not be part of
the mainline project but we, the community of developers working on OSAD, will
be supporting those code basis until they're EOL'd by the upstream OpenStack
projects.

This commit is a formal request to add os-ansible-deployment into the
OpenStack namespace as an official project.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/openstack-ansible
[2] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/openstack_ansible_meeting/
[3] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-ansible/
[4] https://github.com/ansible/ansible/pull/9927
[5] https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-extras/pull/123

Change-Id: Id3f6175fcdd4a21019eabca56cd337145ff9c2b0
'}, {'created': '2015-06-12 15:20:59.000000000', 'message': 'Ansible playbooks and roles to deploy OpenStack

commit_message:
Ansible playbooks and roles to deploy OpenStack

Request to add the os-ansible-deployment project to OpenStack namespace.
os-ansible-deployment (OSAD) is a project dedicated to deploying OpenStack
clouds using Ansible and upstream OpenStack source code without the addition
of vendor driven packaging.

This project is already using all of the OpenStack infrastructure and services
and is gated through gerrit with testing being done on the whole stack using
tempest on our three supported branches.

We are committed to furthering our mission of a great
developer/deployer/operator experience and intend to build out the system to
support all of the OpenStack named services.

We use the OpenStack dev/operators mailing list (albeit infrequently) and hold
meetings twice weekly[1] (one in our channel and the other in an official
OpenStack meeting channel which is logged[2]).

The IRC channel #openstack-ansible is logged[3], and active with community
members, core developers and like minted people all helping and disusing issues
within the project as well as questions that come us from using Ansible to
operate and manage clouds.

The scope of os-ansible-deployment is to provide tooling for deploying OpenStack
using ansible which will include contributing to the efforts of upstream
Ansible. We are already working with the community to ensure that our efforts
are not duplicated or being made in direct contrast to what upstream Ansible is
already providing. While we do have some overlap within our currently carried
modules, the OpenStack client modules we have in tree, we are committed to moving
that functionality and code into upstream just as we've done with our other
plugins/modules[4][5].

With this project's move to "big tent" we'd only be looking to bring with us the
Master and Kilo branches as they've been designed to be community code with
all of the original Rackspace-isms removed. This would mean that the Juno and
Icehouse branches would be left behind in StackForge as they'd not be part of
the mainline project but we, the community of developers working on OSAD, will
be supporting those code bases until they're EOL'd by the upstream OpenStack
projects.

This commit is a formal request to add os-ansible-deployment into the
OpenStack namespace as an official project.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/openstack-ansible
[2] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/openstack_ansible_meeting/
[3] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-ansible/
[4] https://github.com/ansible/ansible/pull/9927
[5] https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-extras/pull/123

Change-Id: Id3f6175fcdd4a21019eabca56cd337145ff9c2b0

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-23 16:19:56.000000000', 'message': 'Fix OSProfiler exception when is enabled

When OSProfiler is enabled in glance-api.conf or glance-registry.conf,
the services are failing to start. They raise an AtttributeError
exception when not finding messaging module from notifier

Closes-Bug: #1467982

Change-Id: I87c0d4f0885f5714e966218eabf06134772babfa
Signed-off-by: Munoz, Obed N <obed.n.munoz@intel.com>
'}, {'created': '2015-06-23 16:37:56.000000000', 'message': "Fix OSProfiler exception when is enabled

When OSProfiler is enabled in glance-api.conf or glance-registry.conf,
the services are failing to start. They raise an AtttributeError
exception when not finding messaging module from notifier

When oslo removed namespaced packages in kilo, the code was changed
in glance.notifier from doing

	from oslo import messaging

To doing

        import oslo_messaging

And all references were changed from messaging to oslo_messaging. When
osprofiler integration was added, the author choose to use the notifier
module's reference to oslo.messaging instead of importing it directly.
When the rename occurred, this was not caught. So, oslo_messaging is
directly imported in glance.cmd.{api,registry} and use it as
it was intended

Closes-Bug: #1467982

Change-Id: I87c0d4f0885f5714e966218eabf06134772babfa
Signed-off-by: Munoz, Obed N <obed.n.munoz@intel.com>

And all references were changed from messaging to oslo_messaging. When
osprofiler integration was added, the author choose to use the notifier
module's reference to oslo.messaging instead of importing it directly.
When the rename occurred, this was not caught. So, oslo_messaging is
directly imported in glance.cmd.{api,registry,search} and use it as
it was intended

Closes-Bug: #1467982

Change-Id: I87c0d4f0885f5714e966218eabf06134772babfa
Signed-off-by: Munoz, Obed N <obed.n.munoz@intel.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Fix OSProfiler exception when is enabled

When OSProfiler is enabled in glance-api.conf or glance-registry.conf,
the services are failing to start. They raise an AtttributeError
exception when not finding messaging module from notifier

When oslo removed namespaced packages in kilo, the code was changed
in glance.notifier from doing

	from oslo import messaging

To doing

        import oslo_messaging

And all references were changed from messaging to oslo_messaging. When
osprofiler integration was added, the author choose to use the notifier
module's reference to oslo.messaging instead of importing it directly.
When the rename occurred, this was not caught. So, oslo_messaging is
directly imported in glance.cmd.{api,registry,search} and use it as
it was intended

Closes-Bug: #1467982

Change-Id: I87c0d4f0885f5714e966218eabf06134772babfa
Signed-off-by: Munoz, Obed N <obed.n.munoz@intel.com>

commit_message:
Cap oslo.il8n to allow for transition away from oslo namespace

This commit adds a version cap to prevent pulling in oslo.il8n v2.0.0.
This latest release removed the namespace package which breaks
glance_store and a bunch of the clients usage of oslo.il8n. We need to
stop using this release (and all future versions of oslo.il8n) until
all the packages we depend on using the oslo namespace for the il8n
module are fixed.

Change-Id: I775fe85bb320a819e32e33b7097332dd75b4aa98

commit_message:
Use sudo to move hook script logs

Hook script retention was failing on neutron-dsvm-functional jobs
due to permission failure.  This change uses sudo ensure that
hook script logs are always retained, which seems to be the common
pattern for test artifact retention.

Change-Id: Ic855b79a657245896aa74fc274d3b8e72ab3a507

ipset to raise an error as it does not work with zero prefix sizes.
To solve this problem we use two ipset rules to represent this.

This was correctly fixed in a backport to kilo though we did not have the
cycles to backport this exact fix to juno as in juno additional work needs to
be done because the iptable and ipset code are interleaved together. This
patch fixes this issue by disabling one from creating an address pair of
zero lenght. This patch also provides a small tool which one should run:
tools/fix_zero_length_ip_prefix.py which changes all zero length address_pair
rules into two address pair rules of:

commit_message:
Disable allowed_address_pair ip 0.0.0.0/0 ::/0 for ipset

Previously, the ipset_manager would pass in 0.0.0.0/0 or ::/0 if
these addresses were inputted as allowed address pairs. This causes
ipset to raise an error as it does not work with zero prefix sizes.
To solve this problem we use two ipset rules to represent this.

This was correctly fixed in a backport to kilo though we did not have the
cycles to backport this exact fix to juno as in juno additional work needs to
be done because the iptable and ipset code are interleaved together. This
patch fixes this issue by disabling one from creating an address pair of
zero lenght. This patch also provides a small tool which one should run:
tools/fix_zero_length_ip_prefix.py which changes all zero length address_pair
rules into two address pair rules of:

Ipv4: 0.0.0.0/1 and 128.0.0.1/1
IPv6: ::/1' and '8000::/1

to avoid the problem.
After this patch is merged into juno it will be easier for us to apply
a better change to allow /0 addresses again in juno.

Change-Id: I8c6a08e0cf3b5b5386fe03af9f2174c666b8ac75
Closes-bug: 1461054
Co-Authored-by: Darragh O'Reilly <darragh.oreilly@hp.com>

commit_message:
Mask database.event_connection details in logs

In notification and collector logs, database connection
details are masked, but other connection strings are not.

This fix masks the event_connection, metering_connection
and alarm_connection strings.

Change-Id: Ib1fdc02e0c0d9cca1201f8304db4584d14498de1
Closes-Bug: #1456263
(cherry picked from commit d05a8f0a37689c6c44a4d91725a3b14135c07eb4)

Remove db layer hard-code permission checks for security_group_default_rule_destroy

security_group_default_rule_destroy.

Partially implements bp nova-api-policy-final-part

commit_message:
Register the vnc config options under group 'vnc'

Also renamed 'vnc_enabled' to 'enabled', and 'vnc_keymap' to 'keymap' now
that those options are prefixed by the 'vnc' group.

Change-Id: I2ff668d4ebd8e6ebf9bf4e8ca5b077958f051144
Closes-Bug: #1447528

I'm still having a hard time understanding the motivation or usefulness of this tag I guess.  The arguments of pets/cattle that comes up also seems off topic.

I think the reality is to be able to spin up VM's you need Nova, and I guess maybe Glance... that's pretty much it.  You can configure no-auth, you can use nova-net.  The DNS as a service seems odd to even consider.

The tag in my opinion just goes back to saying "here's the *important* projects", just another way of doing "integrated" or whatever except you make it easy to keep things out.

Still can't help but wonder if the big tent, all project are beautiful is the right approach.  Maybe Big Tent with "Infrastructure/Base" and "stuff that consumes it" is a better way to go here.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-05-12 18:29:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I'm kinda with John G on this one. I'm having a bit of trouble with the broad definition of a tag that is actually meant to be very limited :)

Going to put some more thought into this one and possibly propose an alternative, but bottom line, I think this tag definition is mixing too many concepts together that it may end up being confusing to the intended audience of operators/deployers.

Best,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-05-13 00:13:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I guess I end up confused by the statement of this mixing too many things, but it might be my perspective. I'm thinking about being inside the head of a small college IT person.

"This cloud thing, I should try it, where do I start?

Clouds run VMs, I'd like to do that. Oh look, I put the psychology department webserver on it now. Great. That's going to survive a host crash, right?

I've also heard I could just spin up and down things more dynamically, I should try that. Neat. Turns out that works really great for the CS dept to set up a lab for their students."

Basically, I can't really imagine anything other than a very synthetic environment where if you are running the cloud yourself in a private context where both approaches aren't going to be used. (Especially if we want to encourage the exploration of more cloud native applications.) That may be a personal lack of imagination. 

One of the contributing factors that docker is on fire right now is that you can be using it, having never used it before, in the next hour, on your laptop or the server in the corner. OpenStack does more, it's never going to be quite like that. But I think we can get closer if we think about this as a base unit which is digestible, and an easy way to install and upgrade components that expand the scope.

What it's called, I don't really care about. But I do think if we say "this is only an ephermeral cloud", then *meh* why not just use Mesos or Docker. And, honestly, I'd probably go down that path if everything I had was really cloud native. The value in the Nova + Cinder approach is it does both existing workloads well, as well as opens the door for new ones. And if you don't keep that door open you never let people level up and try some interesting cloud native things. And if they never do that, they are never going to care about the rest of the ecosystem that we have. And they should have just bought a vCenter or SystemCenter license.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2015-05-25 11:29:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

FWIW I'm -1 on distinguishing an inner sanctum of projects, formerly known as the ring-zero.

The notion seems to run counter to the positive aspects of the big tent reform.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-05-25 16:29:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Eoghan: It is not an inner sanctum. It is a starter kit. Fact is when you deploy "openstack", you won't deploy 12 projects (integrated release) or 150 (big tent). Unless your use case is swift-only, you will start by deploying Nova and the minimal set of projects that Nova requires. It is important that we answer that question, and the big-tent just makes an answer to that question even more necessary.

When the ops asked us to define that set at their mid-cycle meetups, they just wanted an answer to a "minimal starting point". For a Swift use case it's pretty easy to track (Swift being self-sufficient). For a Nova one, not so much. The set of projects it depends on also tends to evolve as we split more functionality out of it.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-05-26 11:47:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(5 comments)

I didn't comment much on the last meeting because I needed some time to process this through and make sure I had put enough thought on it before saying anything. Now that I've read through the spec, talked to some folks and read the comments on this spec, I believe I've a better understanding of what this spec is trying to achieve and what my opinion is.

I'm personally having a hard time trying to find this tag useful. The questions I have are:

- Do we expect people to solely rely on these tags to actually deploy OpenStack?

If I want to deploy OpenStack, I'd go and read docs regardless of the tag. The tag is basically just telling me what projects I should go and read docs for. However, a proper documentation explaining different deployments (compute, compute + storage, etc) would give me the exact information as the tag does.

But where should projects looking for DBaaS go? Are we going to add a tag for that too? I believe that's part of openstack too. 

- Is this the only tag we'll add in this context?

Are we going to add kernel:database ? or kernel:compute:persistent ? How far through the permutation are we going to go?

If the answer is that this will be the only tag, then I've the feeling that we're going back to classifying OpenStack's projects by importance based on a mission statement that, IMHO, doesn't reflect the current governance model.

- Assuming my previous questions don't make any sense, shouldn't we also assume that the tools out there should also work around this (these?) tags ? Or at least have a knowledge about it? Do we expect them to?

For instance have fuel-web, juju, o-f-i, spinalstack, tripleO being able to deploy "kernel:compute".

As it is right now and with my current understanding, I think we shouldn't have this tag. Please, do enlight me and let me know what I'm missing.

If we go down the road of adding this tag, I think we'll have to also define other groups that may/may not depend on this tag.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2015-05-26 16:58:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@ttx: is such a value judgement from the TC on a "minimal starter kit" actually useful to users relying on opinionated tooling to deploy?

Unless these tags actually leak out into the tooling (which mostly provided from outside the community), how are tags going to be consumed by the large subset of users who are not rolling their own deployment infrastructure?

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-05-26 18:47:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think use-case or scenario would be a helpful tag. Really, this is what happens with the Install Guides already. We have these documented:

1. Three-node architecture with OpenStack Networking (neutron) and optional nodes for Block Storage and Object Storage services.
2. Two-node architecture with legacy networking (nova-network) and optional nodes for Block Storage and Object Storage services.
3. For Object Storage, two storage nodes.

So it would be nice to represent this in tags. If we don't do it as a use-case or scenario (or kernel) tag, the ops team may do this on a service-by-service basis. I'm not opposed to that route either. 

I see value in combinations of projects being documented through tagging."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-05-26 20:02:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

I think John summarised it perfectly:

> The tag in my opinion just goes back to saying "here's the *important* projects", just another way of doing "integrated" or whatever except you make it easy to keep things out.

There is a significant subset of the OpenStack community (and there's reason to think that private cloud operators rolling out vSphere replacements in large enterprises might be overrepresented in both this subset and things like the Ops meetup) who were never happy with the decision to begin accepting projects that weren't split out from Nova into incubation, and I believe that some of them see the move to a big tent as an opportunity to redefine 'core' with a new name, wind the clock back to 2012 and I guess as a bonus eliminate Swift, whose presence as one of the foundational projects was no doubt a nagging reminder that OpenStack was conceived with a different vision from the one they had for it.

For some, those are just second-order effects of the tag, but for others I believe they are are primary goal. Asking the TC to define a core compute tag is like demanding that Henry Ford *personally* paint go-faster racing stripes on your horse: it changes nothing beyond publicly committing the leadership to pursue a course of solving yesterday's problems, tomorrow.

To me this tag is not technical at all, it's purely political. I'm disappointed to see the TC entertaining this (yet again), because in the past it has scrupulously avoided such political questions - for example, by refusing to exclude large parts of OpenStack from DefCore's 'designated sections' to allow non-OpenStack code to be trademarked as OpenStack and telling the board to do its own dirty work if it wanted that. Likewise, if the board wishes to begin marketing OpenStack as a free vSphere replacement, then its composition is designed to balance the obviously political interests involved. The TC is neither structured nor intended to address that question, and I believe should maintain its principled stance of giving such questions a wide berth.

The *technical* consequences of creating this tag are IMHO uniformly negative. The attempt to dress up what is otherwise a naked political tag in technical criteria retrospectively derived from a desired list of pet projects (a process which can be observed shamelessly occurring in the comments) will result in the architecture of the included projects being frozen circa 2012, since any innovation is basically forbidden. Some subset of the projects with plug-in architectures to support OpenStack services (off the top of my head: Horizon, Heat, DevStack, Tempest, python-openstackclient, Mistral, Rally) will likely end up creating two-tier systems where kernel:compute projects are treated specially (in-tree, no namespacing, &c.), in the belief that the TC sanctions or even requires it. Eventually we'll inevitably realise that was a mistake, but in the meantime adoption of other innovations (e.g. containers instead of VMs, shared filesystems instead of block storage, &c.) will have been artificially slowed and deployment will have been made even uglier and less consistent.

If there is anyone present who sees those as desirable first-order effects, I'm not really sure what to say. A former manager of mine had a mantra: "Lead, follow, or get out of the way". I don't want anyone to stop working on making Nova better for all of us, but please consider getting out of the way of those folks whose focus is in a different area. As a member of the developer community I genuinely don't see *any* conflict between those - even if it might appear from the outside that the solution to all our problems is for everyone to just drop everything to work on polishing a small handful of projects, we know that is just not the case.

For those who see this as a harmless piece of documentation for prospective operators, please keep in mind that any official pronouncements from the TC will be parsed and interpreted differently by multiple audiences (developers, operators, the board, journalists, and so on). One of the challenges the TC faces is to craft messages that can go to all of these groups without creating harmful second-order effects. This tag fails to meet that bar. It will inevitably be interpreted as something more than a piece of extremely low-resolution documentation for Nova, even if that is the sole intention in creating it.

Sean mentioned in last week's meeting that he proposed a tag because it was the best idea he had so far for how to communicate to operators a starting point for what services to install. I believe it would be better to use descriptive rather than prescriptive means to communicate it, _even if the same set of projects gets identified as a result_, for the following reasons:

* We avoid the second-order effects of the TC appearing to bless a subset of projects on quasi-technical grounds.
* We can ensure wider representation of the OpenStack community, not just groups who are able to attend something like the ops meetup.
* Changes in how operators deploy OpenStack (e.g. if everyone switches from nova-network to Neutron) will be reflected automatically.

Some examples of how we might do this using e.g. data from the user survey:

* Identify the projects that are most often used together: e.g. in the context of this discussion the correlation between installations of Designate and Cinder could tell you something useful about use cases. (I believe we have all the data required for this from the user survey, and that it wouldn't risk deanonymising anyone.)
* Identify e.g. the top 10 deployment configurations. (I'm not sure if there will be enough similarity to get above the noise level, but it would an interesting exercise regardless.)
* Improve the documentation. If this really is just about documenting the dependencies of Nova and the reason e.g. Swift is not in scope is because it doesn't have any, then it would be about 1000x more discoverable in the Compute section of the install guide than on some obscure governance website. Plus, rather than just a 1-bit in/out designation we could include short descriptions of what those relationships actually are (e.g. "Cinder provides persistent block storage to Nova VMs. Without Cinder, Nova provides only ephemeral storage.")
* Get people to share their actual use cases. Sean's goal of making OpenStack understandable to a small college IT admin is an extremely worthy one. I can't imagine any better way of achieving that than a blog post from a small college IT admin about how they installed OpenStack and what it did from them. That's going to be a lot more discoverable and useful than a list of checkboxes on a governance site somewhere. Even better, get a bunch of small college IT admins to blog about their different setups. Infra has a really interesting use case, maybe Monty could document that. Everyone likes to hear about what CERN is doing. Maybe it could be part of the Superuser initiative. Maybe there could be a mechanism for voting on the most popular ones.


In conclusion, the TC has a big tag hammer and that makes this problem look a bit like a nail. In reality, however, it's going to end up sending a counterproductive and inappropriately political message to just about every group except the one that is the nominal audience. There are plenty of alternative ideas for tackling this problem that haven't even been considered. Let's talk about that instead of repeatedly proposing variants of this tag.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-05-28 13:33:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Whatever the name or the description of a tag, it looks like some will consider any tag that doesn't include their project as a "political" tag. I totally get that we are no longer in the business of blessing "important projects". But personally, I think this tag is now closer from "compute-minimal-requirements" than from "important-projects". If the "kernel:compute" name still feels too valuable, we can change it to something more boring.

Fact is that to deliver basic compute capacity, you have to install more than one project, and the list of projects to install is not necessarily obvious (and will evolve over time as we split more functions out of Nova). So describing this set of projects has tremendous value to our users. 

Fact is, a lot of projects depend on that basic compute capability (including Heat). So describing the list of projects that can be added on top of that basic compute capability is also helpful to our users ("builds-on-top-of-basic-compute" tag). In the same spirit, if more and more projects depend on Heat orchestration capabilities, I could see us defining "heat-minimal-requirements" and "builds-on-top-of-heat" tags to illustrate that.

I can see how some projects can misread the meaning of the tag and consider themselves second-class citizens as a result of that. But developers are really not the primary audience for tags. Tags are for our users to consume, to answer the pressing questions they have. And "what is the minimal set of projects I need to install to deliver basic compute functionality" was identified as one of the questions they have... I would hate it if we failed to provide an answer for that just to preserve some developers feelings.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-05-29 23:40:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

This is not at all about *my* project (and note that you're getting the same feedback from people whose projects are in the club). I can assure you that Heat now has so much momentum with users and operators that it is here to stay regardless, I don't worry about it at all. What I worry about is whether we're going to build a real cloud, where applications have control over their own infrastructure, or just a self-service VM provisioner where you create a VM once and just leave it.

Some people want the latter, and I'd guess that's why they're not happy with the perfectly adequate installation guide documentation - they presumably want a big banner at the top of openstack.org with "OpenStack is a self-service VM provisioner (+ playground for dilettantes)". They're entitled to their opinion, but it's not appropriate for the TC to change OpenStack's mission, which IIRC is something about clouds.

I don't buy that developers will just ignore these tags, or that they should. When we tag stuff with team:diverse-affiliation, we send a message to developers that people are more likely to adopt your project if you have people from diverse affiliations working on it. That seems appropriate to me. As I said before, everything the TC does sends a message to everybody - and that's a huge challenge when everyone has a different context from which to interpret, but it won't be solved by pretending it doesn't exist.

So please don't make this personal. It's not about protecting my feelings, or anyone's feelings. It's about creating a framework in which projects are nudged to make better technical decisions, or at least not nudged to make worse technical decisions. This is surely the entire point of the TC.

At the risk of unfairly singling out a project, I'll give an example: python-openstackclient was designed as a single CLI client for all OpenStack services with no namespacing, and with the plugins centrally maintained in a single repo with only 2 core reviewers. In hindsight, this was a catastrophically bad technical decision. (Of course I know that the project has a *very* long history and, like all of the most catastrophic decisions, it no doubt genuinely seemed like a very good idea at the time.) I gather the core reviewers are now telling people (correctly IMHO) to write their plugins out-of-tree (whence they *are* namespaced). I believe a good technical decision at this point would be to treat the existing plugins the same - move them out-of-tree and make them namespaced. I predict not only that this will not happen, but that this tag will become the bar for inclusion if it is approved.

That's one specific example of a way in which I think this tag could lead to poorer technical decisions. I'm sharing this feedback with the TC because I'm sure that a lot of folks may not have thought about it in this level of detail. I hope that some people who may have assumed this tag was at worst a harmless piece of documentation will now reconsider. But either way, you're getting this feedback from multiple people, including some who are safely ensconced under the waterproof part of the big tent, and I don't think that just dismissing it as sour grapes from people trying to protect their own turf is actually a helpful way of building consensus.

Finally, at no point have I said that we shouldn't address the problem. I _have_ said that I believe the proposed solution is extremely weak when it comes to achieving the stated goal. (How exactly would Sean's hypothetical small college IT admin discover this using Google, vs. discovering a hypothetical blog post about how a small college IT admin uses OpenStack?) And I've also said that I believe it would have significant, negative, second-order effects that totally outweigh the benefits. Every time this has come up I have proposed alternative ways of solving the problem and not once has anyone ever engaged in a discussion of those on their merits. As the objections pile up, someone just posts a new thread or a fresh review and we get to debate some variant of the tag again.

(BTW I see zero value in a heat-minimal-requirements tag and, for the record, Keystone is the only project that would get it.)'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-06-01 13:32:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The debate over this application of tags feels a bit like a referendum on the applicability of tags in any case. There are open questions and doubts on who will take note of the tags and to whom they will be meaningful.

I have to admit that I'm extremely conflicted about this specific tag. It does feel a lot like (not necessarily intentionally) blessing a "waterproof" part of the big tent and a roundabout way of getting a blessed core that is smaller than what the integrated release became. As in that would be a second-order effect of labeling _anything_ a "kernel".

However I think it long past the time where we must figure out some way to focus energy on the parts of openstack that could be described as the fundamental infrastructure of "doing openstack" so that we can have some core thing which is going to be not just good enough but excellent.

Note that neither of these things are directly related to what an operator chooses to install, I'm talking about development focus. I think that's a clue to why tags can be confusing and conflict revealing: I know that we're supposed to be talking about something that is supposed to be about info-for-end-users but I can't help myself, I'm talking about what it means to me.

I want a curious person to be able to rock up to the openstack world and be able to say "give me the bare minimum to try things" and for that bare minimum to be totally wicked sweet awesome. That doesn't have to be limiting for the project that are not in the bare minimum. In fact I think in the long run it can be beneficial. As things stand the apparent quality is low enough (in the bare minimum, for the uninitiated) that there's no particular reason to make the investment to see the awesomeness that beyond the bare minimum can provide. If the on ramp is better then people will get to the awesome sooner and in a better mood.

So in the end I think from me the issue is not whether there is a "kernel" of some kind, but in making sure that it is in fact truly minimal and has a name which suggests that the minimal form is for trialling and gosh isn't that stuff on the near horizon awesome?'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2015-06-01 13:51:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@ttx:

 > Tags are for our users to consume, to answer the pressing questions
 > they have. And "what is the minimal set of projects I need to
 > install to deliver basic compute functionality" was identified as
 > one of the questions they have... I would hate it if we failed to
 > provide an answer for that just to preserve some developers feelings.

One word, documentation.

Sure, tags are the new hammer in the TC toolbox, we all get that.

But the *old* hammer for disseminating information to users, namely documentation, is actually a much better tool getting across any idea with any degree of nuance to it beyond a hard-edged night & day distinction.

And even the compute kernel/ring-zero has some nuance that we need to communicate to users ... Are you a pet-keeper or a cow-herder? Is boot-from-volume going to be useful in your world? Do you need DNS? Are VMs or containers your weapon of choice? You like simple networking or the more complex software-definied variety?  ... etc, etc ad nauseum.

Documentation would be a far better conduit IMO for getting across these questions/distinctions, and also be far more agile in the face of future changes in users' needs and our abilities to meet those needs.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-06-01 20:49:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

[I think it is sad that attempts to describe technical relationships between projects keep getting sidelined by non-technical arguments.]

[Also, I'm going to use compute:* rather than kernel:compute here because I think it describes what we want better.]

Really, there needs to be multiple compute:* tags, if in fact tags are the right way to describe these relationships and requirements.  compute:layer-1 describes the non-optional pieces; compute:layer-2 describes the common configuration, which should also include Swift and Neutron in addition to Cinder and whatever else.  But now thats just a 'cloud' with options.

So lets try again...

compute:required and compute:optional are alternatives, this doc without Cinder would define compute:required.  compute:optional adds the next layer up of stuff, like Cinder, Neutron and Designate, and will vary according to use case.

object-store:required is easy, Swift.  object-store:optional adds Keystone (I don't think anything else fits here?)  baremetal:required is Ironic (Keystone? IDK), etc.  Most of these are trivial, which is why only compute:required is under consideration now."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-06-02 13:29:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think the end game of all of us here is to get as many people using as much of OpenStack as we can, and get as many people using OpenStack as possible. This is in support of this.

For people that are already familiar with OpenStack, an install guide listing tons of projects is fine. They already basically understand what things do and how they might inter relate. They were probably around when there were less OpenStack projects, so they got a view of the world then, and understand the basic assembly.

But right now, new users are provided with a giant wall of decisions before they even get started. Decision paralysis is a real thing (http://www.psmag.com/books-and-culture/i-have-been-staring-at-this-screen-for-hours-please-help-me-how-did-i-get-here-is-this-what-i-really-want-to-read) and it mostly makes people feel stupid and frustrated and want to go somewhere else.

My grand vision isn't kicking projects out. I'm quite frustrated that it keeps being spun that way. My grand vision is a "start here" point for people that don't know what ephemeral or persistent compute are. They don't have use cases. They aren't looking for trademarks. They just want to get started with an open cloud in some way that's going to get them something productive quickly. They are looking for a door to welcome them in. And if they get confused by where that door is, they'll just walk down the street and go find some place else with a better door way in, like Mesos or Docker.

Starting at a minimal compute set is a great door. They can immediately start running VMs. They can start poking at the API. Once they get a grasp on that set of moving parts they can start building up. Bringing in Heat, Sahara, Trove. Realizing that file backed Glance is really limiting, and bring up Swift and migrate their image content over there. This is about providing a starting point and a way to fold in more awesome over time. And do it in bite sized chunks.

Anyone that knows enough to skip this stage can and should. But defining a door to get folks inside our tent and realize it's a cool place to be, and there are lots of interesting things here.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-06-02 15:27:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I actually agree with a lot of Dean's comment. I think if the tag were:

- Named "nova:required" instead of "kernel:compute"
- Under the control of the Nova team, not the TC
- Awarded using only the criterion "Is required to use Nova" instead of all this stuff about which message queue it can be implemented with &c.

then it would indeed be harmless as far as I can see. (If the name were "compute:required" that would not be _so_ much worse, but although we kind of crossed that bridge by giving Nova the official name "OpenStack Compute", there are other ways of computing than VMs (containers, AWS Lambda), the big tent theoretically allows competing implementations, and it would be hard to extend the approach to other projects beyond the ones that already have official names while remaining consistent.)

I'm still not sure this would still be particularly useful in giving people a starting point, or that tags are the most sensible way to capture the dependencies. There was an attempt at gathering this information in JSON format at one point during the discussion:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-October/047710.html

and one of the things we learned is that there are other kinds of relationships beyond strict requirements that are interesting, but can't easily be described when all you have is a single bit.

The next layer (what Dean called "compute:optional") is where it gets tricky: I don't believe there's anything that actually *conflicts* with Nova, so isn't everything not strictly required therefore optional? What seems really useful is to describe the ways that those projects interact with Nova (or any other project) and what that gives you as a result, but now we are out of the realm of single-bit documentation again.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-06-02 16:39:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: TC-Vote-1

This tag may have some value for documentation, but I don't see the value for governance. Now that we have http://git.openstack.org/cgit/stackforge/ops-tags-team/ maybe it should move there."}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-06-09 21:10:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
add compute starter kit tag

This proposes a compute starter kit tag to specify a small number of
projects that are targeted at initial compute deploys by new
operators.

This is an evolution of the tag definition based on feedback provided
by folks that want to consume it, folks in favor, and folks
opposed. It makes for lengthy reading, but attempts to document the
questions that have been raised during the process.

Change-Id: Ie4aefe54a88aff9cebdf44e0e6c3f8ed95aa0d0e

commit_message:
Changes container_execute to container_exec

This is more consistent with the "docker exec" command,
and causes the user to do less typing, which they will appreciate.

Closes-Bug: #1459877
Change-Id: I721059e01fa617dcf63c6205ca63b3f1d7def089

commit_message:
Merge config_drive functional tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges config drive functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled for server tests to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I17d3a057f1cf97241ec7c259c6ce943e7523f0d9

corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges extension-info functional tests.

ExtensionInfoSamplesJsonTest is v3 only, leave it as before.

ExtensionInfoAllSamplesJsonTest, the response data is different,
tag the template files with version.

Change-Id: Id7b7bf08cda58d606325ddb82568a73f0bb99f60

commit_message:
Ensure yum-utils is installed before using yum-config-manager

yum-utils provides yum-config-manager but the check for yum-utils is
currently being done after the first usage of yum-config-manager, which
fails if you don't have yum-utils already installed, so move it up
before the first usage of yum-config-manager.

Putting yum-utils in files/rpms/general doesn't help since
yum-config-manager is used in stack.sh before tools/install_prereqs.sh
is called.

Closes-Bug: #1467270

Change-Id: I74996c76838b7dc50d847e3bedb2d04dc55b4431

commit_message:
Use elevated context for backup destroy

db.backup_destroy requires admin context to mark backup record as
deleted. Commit Icff37261b367463b71a1268be16f9c97f595bf0c removed admin
context passed to backup_destroy method.

This patch uses elevated context to destroy backup.
Change-Id: I75b9e1fff48569a8aa320f2f02914fc7b6665d79
Closes-Bug: #1467167

commit_message:
Add support for parameters to translate template

Some templates can have substitutions for values used throughout
the template. We should expose this feature via the command
line.

partially implements bp openstack-client-heat-translator

Change-Id: Iee4c21285afa77e7e5b36437928b3d62c10e465e

commit_message:
Refactor _confirm_token_bind takes AccessInfo

Rather than pass token data in to _confirm_token_bind, pass the
AccessInfo.

This makes one less place where the token data is needed.

commit_message:
Remove not-currently-required amtterm dependency

The pxe_amt driver depends on the openwsman libs but not amtterm.
Remove this dependency since it isn't required at the moment and
isn't packaged for the RedHat-family systems we test on.

Change-Id: Ibc734846a580176df026b0929d2f5d52766a540e

commit_message:
Check for and install easy_install

On Ubuntu 14.04 at least, easy_install is not present by default.
We need to check for it, and if its not there, add it so we can
install pip.  Added a comment block noting the bug and rationale
for using the package manager to get a baseline setuptools.

Change-Id: Icf5434e828ce6c15968d1f46c19a9e11b33f4ed6

commit_message:
Move VM state check post VIF required check

The VIF code determines if a VM is in a valid state for a plug vif, and
then determines if a plug vif is needed.  This can lead to odd scenarios
where the plug of the VIF will fail, when in fact no VIF plugs were
actually required.

This change set swaps the checks around to prevent this failure.

Change-Id: Ic759080fa2848eee179f322dd047bce3048624e8
Closes-Bug: 1466698

"}, {'created': '2015-06-23 10:32:35.000000000', 'message': "Don't install pbr in a venv

Because PIP_VIRTUAL_ENV was set for the installation of requirements,
and left around in scope, the installation of pbr no longer happened
in a global context, it instead landed inside the virtual
env. Unsetting the variable after requirements install gets us back to
where we expect.

This was an unintended side effect of the requirements-venv patch.

Change-Id: I2c4cb4305fec81a5fd237edabee78874ccd0da22
"}]
commit_message:
Don't install pbr in a venv

Because PIP_VIRTUAL_ENV was set for the installation of requirements,
and left around in scope, the installation of pbr no longer happened
in a global context, it instead landed inside the virtual
env. Unsetting the variable after requirements install gets us back to
where we expect.

This was an unintended side effect of the requirements-venv patch.

Change-Id: I2c4cb4305fec81a5fd237edabee78874ccd0da22

This repo will be the home for scripts and manifests for functional and
integration testing of the OpenStack Puppet Modules.

(2 comments)

I've never used --config-dir or --config-file, so I could be wrong here, but reading the documentation and your patch, I think there's a misunderstanding of what those arguments actually do.

- config-dir sets a directory where there are files with .conf extension that should be parsed.

- config-file specifies a configuration file path to parse. This can be used multiple times.

So config-dir and config-file are separate ways of defining configuration files, you should not look for any of the config-files in config-dir."}, {'account_id': 14305, 'date': '2015-06-15 14:39:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

(3 comments)

You are right, that bug is not closed in Cinder and you need to catch ConfigDirNotFoundError that oslo_config raises now, but those are just lines 560 to 562 of your patch. The rests of the code should not be there.'}, {'account_id': 14305, 'date': '2015-06-15 16:14:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

The lines 553-559 track the situation when config files are not located in the requested directory --config-dir. In such way we do not allow to silently ignore the case when --config-dir /existing-dir exists but doesn't contain config files."}, {'account_id': 9535, 'date': '2015-06-15 18:14:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

But like I explained in my comment, it should be allowed to silently ignore an empty config directory, at least if you have  configuration files also specified.

And anyway those are 2 different issues that should go in different patches, one is treating non existing directory and the other (which I don't think is a bug) is allowing an empty config-dir.

commit_message:
Handle incorrect '--config-dir' param

This patch fixes the error that occurs if the --config-dir directory
doesn't exist. The exception ConfigDirNotFoundError should be caught
in this case.

Change-Id: Iee3fbd2b01de11124788e2c1df5c456c4010d234
Closes-Bug: #1255354

commit_message:
Fixes missing admin/user for devstack plugin

At some point a VAR we depended on was removed or changed upstream. This
patch updates to fixes that so the users fields are populated again.

Change-Id: Ie58b478d13b758e020df0655e6e3462ab4755f9a

commit_message:
Add handler for ConnectsTo relationship

The ConnectsTo relationship in a node can have an interface that
contains the Configure relationship.  This interface would have
a lifecycle operation associated with it, something like a
configuration script requiring some input parameters.
In the Heat template, each of these lifecycle operation would
be implemented as a software config node.
This patch adds the handler in the main translation loop to
process the ConnectsTo relationship.

Partially Implements: blueprint translate-tosca-monitoring-usecase
Change-Id: I5ca4b935cc8189ac46dca0d24a9aa8b40133928c

commit_message:
changed container bind mounts to use abspath

This change modifies the container create bind mounts to use the
absolute path that would be within the container instead of the
relitive path. This change is being done to ensure that there
are never issues with bind mounts as in newer versions of LXC and
the CGManager the absolute path is required.

Change-Id: I6af23c7ea0a7f905bdd587adde966a449402ed0a
Closes-Bug: #1462068

changed container bind mounts to use abspath

This change modifies the container create bind mounts to use the
absolute path that would be within the container instead of the
relitive path. This change is being done to ensure that there
are never issues with bind mounts as in newer versions of LXC and
the CGManager the absolute path is required.

- gate-oslo-incubator-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/22/193322/1/check/gate-oslo-incubator-python34/fbd9798/ : SUCCESS in 1m 33s'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-06-19 03:20:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I have several concerns here.

Firstly, this isn't consistent: we have several add_ methods and only one is being modified to return the added object. There's no reason to be inconsistent and inconsistent is harder to learn.

Secondly, this makes the implementation of the timer part of the public API, which it wasn't-really before (though you could argue that self.timers was documented). So, this needs some consideration - at minimum we should describe what we want to be tied down to in future (e.g. what methods on the returned thing can be used, or what class it will be if we think that that level of coupling is appropriate).

Thirdly, there's no provision for dealing with already cancelled timers AFAICT: using this is going to cause exceptions to be sprinkled through the logs when stop_timers is called.

So, I'd like to see at a bare minimum those three things addressed."}, {'account_id': 13560, 'date': '2015-06-19 05:13:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@lifeless: There is the add_thread method that returns the thread created, so add_timer isnt the first one to return the added object.

Yes, I was assuming the timer part of the API is publicly usable as in add_timer and stop_timers. So if its not, then i think it should be as its useful.

The return is going to be optional since timers will still be managed internally, but also give an option to those who care or want to stop some timers to achieve a dynamic reload of functionality.'}, {'account_id': 13560, 'date': '2015-06-19 15:07:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-19 15:14:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Return timer after adding it to internal list

In some cases, its useful to selectively stop
some timers and not all. This fix allows a way
for client applications to maintain a handle
on timers and be able to stop some of them
selectively.

This is needed by
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190842/

Change-Id: Ie238615397a8dafe3c1f554d4a5166ad18fc8aca
Closes-Bug: 1466661

commit_message:
Rename image_id to image in container object

Currently, magnum used "image_id" to reflect the image in container,
but actually, we can support use both image name and image id to create
a container. The name "image_id" may confuse user that we only support
"image_id" when create a container.

This patch rename the "image_id" field to "image" in container object.

Change-Id: Ie3639feb2a2a90300662b74f186ef998d38d6cc4
Closes-Bug: #1466278
Closes-Bug: #1465558

commit_message:
Adding unit test coverage for the validate method

Adding a case in the existing unit tests to cover the ValueError
exception in the validate method of the GetInput classs. Also adding
a new yaml.

Change-Id: I9e7845e9ef5be15ea671155b22e60325e296302f
Closes-Bug: #1466657

commit_message:
Make token bind work with a request

The confirm token bind function takes the env dictionary. It should be
like other functions and operate on a request.

Change-Id: Id3bde0ef657cff6d1b2551e5a68245be71ccdb93

commit_message:
Rename _LOG to log in auth_token middleware

With the move to having a base class for auth_token middleware the log
object should be public. Rename the self._LOG attribute (which always
looked funny in caps as an attribute) to self.log.

Change-Id: Ib8050423eb712eb5d99a5be07d1ba5639c8d03c8
