The logging added in commit c13f42e36cddd820b475ffecf1f3a9e894d0cc04
shows that the instance.info_cache.network_info is empty when we fail to
associated a floating IP with an instance.

This change adds more logging in the network layer around things that
would affect the instance_info_cache.network_info value, such as
building the network info model in nova-network and allocate/deallocate
of a fixed IP.

From the logs we have when this fails, get_instance_nw_info is never
returning anything for the instance that fails, which may mean that when
the fixed IP is allocated and associated to the instance, there is a
race where the fixed IP record in the database is disassociated
asynchronously while deallocating from the previous instance it was
associated with.

Related-Bug: #1249065

Change-Id: I42f9af1dabffdc98e69d9eeeab1875098bc71bc0

commit_message:
network: add more debug logging context for race bug 1249065

The logging added in commit c13f42e36cddd820b475ffecf1f3a9e894d0cc04
shows that the instance.info_cache.network_info is empty when we fail to
associated a floating IP with an instance.

This change adds more logging in the network layer around things that
would affect the instance_info_cache.network_info value, such as
building the network info model in nova-network and allocate/deallocate
of a fixed IP.

From the logs we have when this fails, get_instance_nw_info is never
returning anything for the instance that fails, which may mean that when
the fixed IP is allocated and associated to the instance, there is a
race where the fixed IP record in the database is disassociated
asynchronously while deallocating from the previous instance it was
associated with.

Related-Bug: #1249065

Change-Id: I42f9af1dabffdc98e69d9eeeab1875098bc71bc0

commit_message:
Use items() instead of iteritems() for validators

While it may be lighter to iterate, the dict will likely have fewer
than 10 items, so it doesn't have a practical impact. However using
.items() allows python3 compatibility without resorting to including
python-six for now.

Change-Id: I19c44b0501f65a5f834ef34bccbe8f3a8728bd58

commit_message:
Don't rely on set representation

Different versions of Python represent set as different text strings.
Join the values manually instead of relying on local implementation.

Change-Id: Idaab855151eccd140fa2597335c72bade171b71d

commit_message:
Docs: Use RFC5737 for Provider Networking

That'll make things more clear that with the provider networking
feature in DevStack, FIXED_RANGE will be a routed IPv4 subnet that gives
routed IPv4 addresses to instances without using floating IPs.

Change-Id: Ie26d75ac5ff285a25762c4f61fd9800b0382886b

commit_message:
Add support for HGST Solutions volumes to libvirt

Add a LibvirtHGSTVolumeDriver which can use Cinder volumes created
by the HGST volume driver.

Unit tests also added to appropriate class.

Prerequisites:
HGST Solutions needs to be installed and running on Nova node
Cinder patch @ https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186580/
OS-Brick patch @ https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186588/

Change-Id: I3ea615183a926148cb3f562022a0d8a38709f488
Implements: blueprint add-volume-driver-hgst-solutions

commit_message:
Mask database.event_connection details in logs

In notification and collector logs, database connection
details are masked, but other connection strings are not.

This fix masks the event_connection, metering_connection
and alarm_connection strings.

Change-Id: Ib1fdc02e0c0d9cca1201f8304db4584d14498de1
Closes-Bug: #1456263

commit_message:
Edits to dev guide, juno guide, and kilo guide

-Added notes to assist whoever is using the guide for when they run into an error
that I previously encountered (repeatedly). Also changed the basic-config-sample.conf
to clean up the commented lines and added a sample pool configuration.
-Corrected a few typos in the guide for juno, and added clarification on how to
use the mysql command line.

--update2--
Made changes according to Tim's comments.
-Added back the commented lines to config sample file
-Removed Pool Backend Configs
-Added apt-get update to steps
-Updated mysql commands

--update4--
Minor change: deleted repeat in basic-config-sample.conf

--update5--
Added guide for Kilo using the ubuntu-dev guide with modifications as fit for the Kilo branch.

--update7--
-Shortened title
-removed random spacesx

--update8--
-removed line from basic-config file
-created config file specific to kilo
-renamed config file specific to juno
-edited doc with correct config file names

commit_message:
Fix the meter unit types to be consistent

The unit types for certain meters generated from
pollsters are not consistent with the once generated
via notifications. This fix handles the mismatch.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1460696

Change-Id: Ibd82fa4a5a4e66abaf2a6d0bbe18df4fbfac3ffb

[{'created': '2015-06-23 16:09:19.000000000', 'message': "Use oslo_messaging directly for osprofiler

When oslo removed namespaced packages in kilo, we changed our code in
glance.notifier from doing

    from oslo import messaging

To doing

    import oslo_messaging

And we changed all references from messaging to oslo_messaging. When
osprofiler integration was added, the author chose to use the notifier
module's reference to oslo.messaging instead of importing it directly.
When the rename occurred, this was not caught. So we import
oslo_messaging directly in glance.cmd.api and use it as it was intended

Closes-bug: 1467982
Change-Id: I32263252ee8d7fd9b70965ab967c4a2c33c928af
"}]
commit_message:
Use oslo_messaging directly for osprofiler

When oslo removed namespaced packages in kilo, we changed our code in
glance.notifier from doing

    from oslo import messaging

To doing

    import oslo_messaging

And we changed all references from messaging to oslo_messaging. When
osprofiler integration was added, the author chose to use the notifier
module's reference to oslo.messaging instead of importing it directly.
When the rename occurred, this was not caught. So we import
oslo_messaging directly in glance.cmd.api and use it as it was intended

Closes-bug: 1467982
Change-Id: I32263252ee8d7fd9b70965ab967c4a2c33c928af

commit_message:
Move Server.created to created_at

Other resources have timestamps with an "_at" suffix, which makes more
sense to converge on than without the suffix, otherwise it looks like a
boolean name.

Change-Id: I9097d0309ce3bbf6340fbce623321c6d41cf57c7
Closes-Bug: 1435880

commit_message:
Add support for deploying Keystone with Fernet

This change adds a number of new tasks that are dependent on the value
of the Keystone token provider (keystone_token_provider) user variable.

If the keystone_token_provider user_variable is set to
keystone.token.providers.fernet.Provider then the playbooks will
appropriately create the fernet keys and distribute them to the rest of
the keystone containers.

This also implements key rotation for generated fernet keys similar to
how the os_nova roles implement key rotation.

Finally, we also need to build cryptography from master for now.
Currently, 0.8.x and 0.9.x use versions of cffi<1.0 which causes a bug
when used with mod_wsgi and Apache. This is fixed in cryptography master
and will be released in 1.0.

Closes-bug: 1463569
Change-Id: I8605e0490a8889d57c6b1b7e03e078fb0da978ab
(cherry picked from commit 9ad608a53585d3cbddb2e834188059dae7d01979)

commit_message:
Revert "Adding support for neutron-debug CLI."

There isn't a reason to have a function to call this command
live in tempest-lib. The neutron-debug CLI is only used for
local debug and isn't actually a client. It's for running
locally on the same node as neutron. It's completely out of
scope for living in tempest-lib. Just because there is a
CLI for something in an OpenStack project running doesn't
mean we need to have a dedicated function to call it. It's
a simple matter to locally subclass the CLIClient class and
add local functions to call commands for a particular test
suite. 

So let's revert this before it's included in a release. If
it were to be included in a release the effort to remove it
goes up quite a bit, because we need a proper deprecation
cycle.

This reverts commit 43c45b2b9dc6b5369556feb94431ed3e22185d34.

Change-Id: I8e77dd92abd482e6cdbaceff81dc12b9f224e2ec

commit_message:
Add logic to pass sg and sg-rules to ODL

This adds back the code to pass sg and sg-rules into ODL. In addition
to the original code, this also utilizes method functions instead of
module functions, as weakref is now supported in the callback
layer.

This reverts commit d446fcd8f01e5d210b5c43f34ed9241fe31f663a.

Change-Id: I4c22db3b3d78ba060d55ea759d8751115bf9df57
Co-Authored-By: Flavio Fernandes <ffernand@redhat.com>
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
oslo incubator sync

Import the latest oslo incubator code.
Imported from commit f2cfbba78c0bfb5d48f32d86182f3e39f317ec82

openstack.common.log is used only by openstack.common.policy now.
It can be deleted when Horizon consumes policy from openstack_auth.
Until then we need to keep openstack.common.log in the tree.

Change-Id: I716625b4ae44da7bb0372af82b48ac5e06266616

commit_message:
Add id function extractor to datasource driver

Previously, there was no way to build a custom identifier
when translating an API call result into tables.  The
only options were to specify a column name or to have
an ID generated for you.

This change makes it possible to specify a function that
given the object returns an ID.

Implements-blueprint: datasource-driver-custom-id
Change-Id: I9ff134ef56fb118ba846fcdef11a656e25435df6

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-11-20 12:37:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2

(2 comments)

I am very happy about the idea of us supporting this feature in Nova.
But I am quite strongly against this being an extra API.

Can't this just be an image property? If not, please describe why that is no sufficient, and I will happy remove my -2

To me, the user should get the best performance for the host and image combination they get given. It shouldn't be something they need to manually configure, we should give them the correct configuration (i.e. match the threads to the vCPUs in the request flavor)."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-11-20 14:01:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

The reason we can't enable this unconditionally at a fixed number of queues is given in the problem description of the spec. Specifically we have a finite resource of MSI vectors and each queue consumes one of these. We cannot blindly enable this on all NICs or we'd be limiting the number of devices that guest can use."}, {'account_id': 3217, 'date': '2014-11-26 22:49:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

If there is a finite number of queues, isn't this a limitation that should be scheduled for?  And wouldn't it also apply to stock singlequeue VMs as well?

On where it should be, my $0.02 is that the image would express its support for multiqueue for the purposes of starting the VM, and potentially preventing scheduling in the case of an incompatibility, and the flavour would express the number of queues to be made available iff they're a limited resource.  We shouldn't be scheduling a limited resource based on the user's opinion alone because that way leads DoS attacks.  (I shall read the spec, I promise, but I thought I'd say this first.)"}, {'account_id': 6772, 'date': '2014-11-28 17:18:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The limit is in terms of what a guest can recognize/use, not in terms of what the host can expose.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-12-03 17:43:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(4 comments)

I like the comments from danb here that describe the use cases in more detail. We need that adding in the spec.

Look at adding this extra data into the port create on boot, I think we need some more thought on the API impact of that, I would personally make that a second spec/blueprint that depends on this spec.

About the API, I think we need to carefully describe that attach interface and boot both need this extra parameter about the port.

I do wonder if that info should go to neutron, but in this case, its nova specific, so I guess it shouldn't be stored in neutron. If thats the case, we need to describe where it will be stored, as network_info_cache today is constructed only from information that comes from neutron."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-12-03 17:46:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

to be clear, I think I get the need for the API, if we explain the use cases better.

But I am keeping the -2 because I don't think the API is defined well enough.

My preference would be to split this into two, one blueprint for the basic support (always specified in the flavor), and a second blueprint for the port related API."}, {'account_id': 13869, 'date': '2014-12-05 13:47:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8802, 'date': '2014-12-09 21:36:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

I will update the use story, as suggested, however, I don't see a point of splitting the blueprint.
I think it has a lot of value when the whole feature is explained in one document.

Also, I don't understand why is the a -2.
AFAIU, -2 means something along the lines of "stop working on this feature, it doesn't make any sense." Isn't it?'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-12-10 09:45:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I agree with keeping this as one blueprint - splitting it up is really not productive / useful.'}, {'account_id': 13869, 'date': '2014-12-10 14:55:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I think it could be useful to have a spec similar to api-specify-vnic-type (see https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/api-specify-vnic-type) for a new parameter: vnic_options.

The vnic_options could be used to pass specific parameters to a nic like the number of queues or other like offloading options.'}, {'account_id': 8802, 'date': '2014-12-12 17:07:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-12 17:17:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

(1 comment)

Sorry to have been away for a while from this, but per sgordon's clarification I think flavour is the wrong place for this.

A sysadmin doesn't care how many queues you use, in much the same way as they don't care how many NICs you use; you'll just get a failure to spawn if you use too many (of either)."}, {'account_id': 8802, 'date': '2014-12-15 17:01:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

As I mentioned in the inline comment, the current idea is to have this feature enabled by default, and let the admin have control over it.
If the admin didn't have any control, then there is no reason to expose it in the image properties, as the user can control the feature from the api, according to the current design."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-12-16 14:42:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

[{'created': '2015-06-11 11:09:20.000000000', 'message': "Decouple ObjectVersionChecker and VersionedObjectRegistry

ObjectVersionChecker just needs a list of classes, we don't need
to check the base.VersionedObjectRegistry everytime, so just
initialize the list of classes in the constructor and default
it to the base.VersionedObjectRegistry to get the current
behavior. Will make it easy to run ObjectVersionChecker against
custom registries.

Change-Id: I700daa278473dff5285e0b21afffc03671e390f9
"}]
commit_message:
Decouple ObjectVersionChecker and VersionedObjectRegistry

ObjectVersionChecker just needs a list of classes, we don't need
to check the base.VersionedObjectRegistry everytime, so just
initialize the list of classes in the constructor and default
it to the base.VersionedObjectRegistry to get the current
behavior. Will make it easy to run ObjectVersionChecker against
custom registries.

Change-Id: I700daa278473dff5285e0b21afffc03671e390f9

commit_message:
Add disk layout check on re-provisioning

The preserve ephemeral logic does not check whether the
disk layout was changed since the last time the node was
provisioned. Additionally we have introduced a 
driver_internal_info['instance'] object to store instance's
disk configration and which is purged when tearing down an
instance.

Change-Id: Iecdb8db37b22c37275be3197950bbf899aa62a53
Closes-Bug: #1327260

The tag is about common series-related stable branches (think stable/kilo), maintained by the stable maintenance team according to the stable branch policy. So it does not really apply here ? At least not until you use stable/$series for Gnocchi ?'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-06-19 14:25:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Gnocchi actually matches the requirements described by the tag. So somehow it's likely the tag requirements are not enough. I think it's sad to let think that project does not have stable branches because some team does not maintain them, but well."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-19 16:20:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Maybe we need two tags. The thing is, if each project can have different stable branches with different stable branch policies (acceptable patches etc.), then "stable branch" doesn't mean anything anymore...'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-06-23 14:15:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Yes, the release team is going to work on clarifying the language for the existing stable tag and add another tag defined more closely to the way gnocchi manages back ports.'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-06-23 15:15:58.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Abandonning based on Doug's comment."}]

commit_message:
Sync amqp support with other openstack modules

Kilo oslo-messaging deprecates rabbit/kombu settings in the
DEFAULT section.

Rabbitmq won't talk to us anymore if we try to use SSLv3 as it disabled
support for SSLv3. Openstack components use python's openssl
implementation which does not support TLSv1.1 and TLSv1.2 yet so we
just switch to TLSv1. Support for newer TLS should come with python
2.7.9+

The kombu_ssl_* parameters should not be required when rabbit_use_ssl => true
Rather, rabbit_use_ssl must be set to true if the kombu_ssl_* parameters are
used.

Change-Id: I327dc193d878cb1574b69d5f5b502c25fa203a66
Closes-Bug: #1409667
Closes-Bug: #1356083

commit_message:
Introduce public_url(_s3), internal_url(_s3) and admin_url(_s3)

This change deprecates the following parameters:
- endpoint_prefix: replaced by public/internal/admin_url
- port: replaced by public/internal/admin_url(_s3)
- public_port: replaced by public_url(_s3)
- public_protocol:  replaced by public_url(_s3)
- public_address: replaced by public_url(_s3)
- public_port: replaced by public_url
- internal_protocol: replaced by internal_url
- internal_address: replaced by internal_url
- admin_protocol: replaced by admin_url
- admin_address: replaced by admin_url

Add deprecation warnings if any of those values are provided
while maintaining full backward compatibility.

Co-Authored-By: David Moreau Simard <dmsimard@iweb.com>
Co-Authored-By: Richard Raseley <richard@raseley.com>
Closes-bug: #1274979
Change-Id: Ie4afc21ac6e9539edd70635de7f3db957a22467e

(1 comment)

Note I proposed this change as it was suggested in IRC as a potential solution to the problem. I'm not entirely a fan though of forcing non-PBR-using (even non-Python-at-all) repos to use PBR's notion of PEP-440/semver normalized form for all pre-release and release tags."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-05-06 18:45:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2015-05-06 18:46:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-06-23 14:13:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The actual problem that we would like to solve is to prevent people from creating or pushing tags which are different than what pbr will use for the version.  This won't do that -- it's too late in the process.  Instead, this will merely prevent us from creating a tarball.  If we change nothing, we can, if we choose, simply go and delete the mis-generated tarball.  But in no case can we reverse the applied tag without consequences.

On the other hand, this will increase the complexity in the zuul configuration and may cause people to put ther release jobs in the wrong pipeline and wonder why they did not run."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2015-06-23 14:57:32.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

At this point I'm fairly convinced that tag review (probably with a validation job reporting on each proposed tag) is the only way we're going to "solve" the problem.'}]

commit_message:
Only support PBR>=0.11.0 semver release tags

With the advent of PBR 0.11.0 all repos using it generate
3-component release or 4-component pre-release versioned tarballs
and wheels. Our release automation driven from Zuul needs to be able
to assume that the versions on these artifacts match the tags
themselves. Restrict triggering the pre-release and release
pipelines to only tags in a format PBR>=0.11.0 will generate.

Change-Id: I7ffdeee8a398a4914e1566de4c2cc7f637da6ec9

What about adding of possibility to set Nova AZ using qualified extra spec in addition to configuration option. Extra spec will have first priority and configuration option will be second? It will allow user to choose Nova AZ if he likes, and admin to specify fall-back AZ if he needs to.'}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2015-05-27 18:58:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think the extra_spec approach is a better option than hardcoding it in the config. However, if we were to combine the 2 approaches, then I think I would do that by making the driver return a capability indicating which AZ it was pinned to, so that the scheduelr could filter on that with unqualified extra specs.

Still, I think a more comprehensive approach to the AZ problem is needed.'}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2015-06-19 15:14:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The current thinking is that each Manila backend should be in exactly 1 AZ. The rationale is this:

Availability Zones are assumed to be a failure domain. It's reasonable to assume that entire AZs can fail as a unit due to a power outage or similar problem.

Therefore if the manila-share service responsible for managing a share is in a different AZ than the actual share (in the generic driver case, the AZ where the nova instance and cinder volume are) then a failure of the AZ where the manila-share service is would cause loss of access to the share even though the AZ where the share exists was still fine.

It's better to require that the manila-share service runs in the same AZ that the shares it creates exist in. This will result in a model where there is a separate instance of the generic driver per AZ. This is moderately wasteful of resources, but will result in better user experiences in multi-AZ clouds running manila with the generic driver."}, {'account_id': 11865, 'date': '2015-06-19 18:02:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

FWIW, I'm writing a Manila AZ design spec now.  We will need to support AZs in the generic driver, but probably not in the way proposed here."}, {'account_id': 14232, 'date': '2015-06-23 14:57:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2015-05-08 20:08:53.000000000', 'message': 'Asynchronous Zone Import

* Creates /v2/zones/tasks/imports, which allows users to view imports as resources
* Brings back export in /v2/zones/id/tasks/export unchanged
* Creates new database table zone_tasks for asynchronous tasks related to zones, along
with the associated objects/adapters
* Imports are done by passing over the request body, creating an async record in the db,
and spawning a thread to do the import

Implements: async-import-export
APIImpact: Adds /zones/tasks/imports and brings back /zones/id/tasks/export
    from admin API

commit_message:
Asynchronous Zone Import

* Creates /v2/zones/tasks/imports, which allows users to view imports as resources
* Creates new database table zone_tasks for asynchronous tasks related to zones, along
with the associated objects/adapters
* Imports are done by passing over the request body, creating an async record in the db,
and spawning a thread to do the import
* Adds a config option to enable zone import

Implements: async-import-export
APIImpact: Adds /zones/tasks/imports and removes import from admin api

Change-Id: Ib23810bf8b25d962b9d2d75e042bb097f3c12f7a

commit_message:
Add manage_service parameter to all agents::ml2 classes that did not yet have it.

This existed in the older agents::ovs and agents::linuxbridge classes
which were recently removed, adding here for consistency.

When set to false, enables puppet to configure a service without
starting/stopping it on each run.  This may be necessary when
using an external clustering system (Corosync/Pacemaker, for
example).  Defaults to true.

Change-Id: I3242f790e7d3231a81b447c10aa2d741b7b68a3e

The 86th line of http://docs.openstack.org/juno/config-reference/content/section_cinder.conf.html follows "implicit" path, while puppet-cinder evaluates it explicitly with double quotes.'}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-06-16 09:50:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-06-16 09:56:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Looks like spec assumes that values are substituted by Puppet, so I think I have the answer now.'}, {'account_id': 7745, 'date': '2015-06-16 10:09:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The problem is that tests are failed because they substitute  $rabbit_host:$rabbit_port , but expecting localhost:5672. And conf rabbit_hosts contains $rabbit_host:$rabbit_port (it's ok: http://docs.openstack.org/kilo/config-reference/content/ch_configuring-sahara.html). But we have failed tests.
We have to solutions for this situation: we can explicitly set $rabbit_host:$rabbit_port to spec, or we can use double quotes in puppet manifest.

Which one will be correct?"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2015-06-16 12:26:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 14007, 'date': '2015-06-19 08:30:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7604, 'date': '2015-06-19 08:36:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7732, 'date': '2015-06-19 08:36:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 15313, 'date': '2015-06-19 18:47:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7155, 'date': '2015-06-23 14:30:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-23 14:31:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

Enable tests for oslo_messaging_rabbit/rabbit_hosts parameter

The problem is that value for this parameter quotes in quote ',
but it should be double quotes ".

commit_message:
Revert "glance provider: pick os_region_name from DEFAULT"

This reverts commit b76fbcbea34b510191964cc3ed6a4c8e6f2acbfe.

With 268370457c118e62b93990cea31066c477ab0dbc now merged, we need to go
back to looking for os_region_name in [glance_store] instead of
[DEFAULT].

Change-Id: I197d012387d630ca6fb3a38c48f0603add6c6de1

commit_message:
Always allow removing instance_uuid from node in maintenance mode

This will help to dissociate node from nova instance in cases like
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1229401

Closes-Bug: #1465153
Change-Id: I9c736612d7a526e58ea2af5e7296e80354550bdc

commit_message:
cells: add devstack/tempest-dsvm-cells-rc for gating

We need to whittle down the large regex of excluded tests for the
tempest-dsvm-cells job but we also need to be able to test changes to
the regex, like removing entries that we think are now working.

This change moves the regex from project-config in the
tempest-dsvm-cells job definition to nova so that nova can control and
test the changes on it's own, since project-config is not currently able
to self-test job changes.

project-config change: I8cbc36266eadaf0dbef20e3e83f4874bcfc9ab3a

Change-Id: I2365619de4ba7b43a049771bac90d2deebaa3e9c

commit_message:
Fix version determination in corner cases

The initial "version = " grep could pick up extra lines. Anchor it
at the start of the line so that it only gets "version = " and not
"foobar.version = ".

Change-Id: I5289a0a0997fc1618b65bcf1c9a5577bc7094cb7

To further align with the canonical form of PEP440, pre-versions
leading to $VERSION should no longer be ${VERSION}b1 but
${VERSION}.0b1.

Change-Id: Ic0bb8f5e9ba31370cd495f4396eb1b1306e06911
'}]
commit_message:
upload_release.py should use $VERSION.0b1 too

To further align with the canonical form of PEP440, pre-versions
leading to $VERSION should no longer be ${VERSION}b1 but
${VERSION}.0b1.

The logic to determine that is duplicated in upload_release.py, so
until we rearchitect that that needs to be fixed there too.

commit_message:
Could not find resource Service[undef] for relationship from Package.

Original variables were not assign any value. Therefore puppet will try
to find Service[undef].

Adjust those service's title to correctly parameter location at
ceilometer's class.

Change-Id: Ibef8410848076bc0bc7d7824b28e93efad02a231
Closes-Bug: #1455029

commit_message:
Fixes create user example output

The output of command 'openstack user create' doesn't have 'project_id',
remove it from the example output.

Closes-bug: #1466411

commit_message:
Spark doc references vanilla diskimagebuilder page

"The Spark plugin has been developed and tested with the images
generated by the _Building Images for Vanilla Plugin_." rename
diskimagebuilder to avoid misunderstanding

Change-Id: Idb01707aa5d1982413560961d3a08aa10fdc7aa0
Closes-bug: 1462133

commit_message:
Pre-versions are now $VERSION.0b1

To further align with the canonical form of PEP440, pre-versions
leading to $VERSION should no longer be ${VERSION}b1 but
${VERSION}.0b1.

NB: rcdelivery.sh will need a similar fix when we rewrite it to
support separate server versioning.

Change-Id: Id8c491ee19291398a26cda41f1f64de8bb4644be

commit_message:
Raise correct exception on missing attribute

Python2 required any exception raised for hasattr(). Python3 requires
specifically AttributeError.

Change-Id: I1e4ba0617e3cdf6109baf13dc503cd31ffe59df3

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fixes method retrieving free SCSI controller slot on V1

The method retrieving a free SCSI controller slot gets all the
related disk resources, checking their address using the
AddressOnParent attribute.

The issue is that this WMI object attribute is not available on the
V1 virtualization namespace, for which reason this method will raise
an AttributeError in case there disks connected to the SCSI
controller.

This patch fixes the issue by properly retrieving the disk address.

Closes-Bug: #1467916

Change-Id: I7f88e37ac6d13cd8a15b17939ec8dbdca2c988e1
(cherry picked from commit 209a7fd2285fbcdafe66d1218dd3874ed51dde78)

commit_message:
Add doc warning to engine components

These components are internal to an engine and should
not be used externally so make sure we add a doc note
that states this (or at least warns about using them
minimally).

There are still useful to document as they are used
in docs that describe how engines work and what they
do.

Change-Id: I9143f5d7114ccedddee602dabff4b48446bd99ff

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-04 07:38:05.000000000', 'message': 'Do not update existing image on create by default

Openstack image create command updates existing image (with same name) by

commit_message:
Do not update existing image on create by default

Openstack image create command updates existing image (with same name) by
default. Glance client allow create multiple images with same name, what
can lead to unwanted update of existing image when creating a new one.

Parameter --or-update was added to openstack image create to allow
update existing image, otherwise image create does not update existing
image with same name.

Change-Id: Ib521ef628da2ccb8d50a4e7a8bb1c5f81cb2b3f6
Closes-Bug: #1461817

commit_message:
Opencontrail: Create neutron::plugins::opencontrail

Create the neutron::plugins::opencontrail class that allows one to
configure neutron to work with opencontrail. The parameters have been
taken from here[1]

[1]
https://github.com/Juniper/contrail-neutron-plugin/blob/master/etc/neutron/plugins/opencontrail/ContrailPlugin.ini

Change-Id: I080c4aed23ebde320e67c98c44171b18bf2758ad

commit_message:
Switch to oslo_serialization

oslo.serialization 1.2.0 has moved its namespace from old
oslo.serialization to oslo_serialization, the old import style can
still work, but will not be supported in next release cycle.

Change-Id: If271b6d20b0b87ff0de0776dcaaba04a17193885

commit_message:
Sync 'report' from oslo-incubator

Needed to fix guru meditation report for Windows.
We landed an outdated 'report' module recently.

Add report.[generators,models,views] to
openstack-common.conf.

Oslo source: c4c7dd28 Updated from global requirements

Closes-Bug: #1286528

Change-Id: Ib33542718176241663c0e61605acbf4e941e2ca9

commit_message:
Add --prefix to override .buildconf

Add in the ability to override the prefix in .buildconf files removing
the requirement to set the prefix in a .buildconf to limit the number
of images built.

Partially Implements: blueprint refactor-base-image-layout

Change-Id: I1da1559e660adc2fe9eaf5e17ce427c89645a8b7

commit_message:
Removes lockfile from requirements

It doesn't look like murano in stable/kilo uses lockfile.
This patch removes it from requirements. Note that lockfile
is currently a problem because version 0.9 is incompatible
with the old API of v 0.8, so I'd prefer to get this unstable
requirement removed.

Change-Id: I2ff2e35de12418790f1c4669d4c316b08408d6b7

commit_message:
Make use of devstack external plugin

Instead of copying files manually to devstack it much
easier to use the devstack external plugin interface [1].
This makes the usage of Murano much easier for developers.

The plugin.sh script is a copy of contrib/devstack/lib/*
and contrib/devstack/extras.d/70-murano.sh. These scripts
can be removed after the CI system is switch to the new
model.

[1]: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/devstack/plugins.html#externally-hosted-plugins

Change-Id: I9fc24d17301947f5a95c139576037efc679d4bc4
Implements: bp use-devstack-plugin

commit_message:
Add 2 callbacks to processutils.execute()

Add optional on_execute and on_completion callbacks to allow callers of
procesutils.execute() to track process completion asynchronously.

This could be used to cache the pid of long running tasks associated
with an instance and then clear the cache when the process completes.
While the tasks are running should it be required the pid retrieved and
the process can be signaled.

Conflicts:
        oslo_concurrency/processutils.py

Co-Authored-By: abhishekkekane <abhishek.kekane@nttdata.com>
Change-Id: Ifc23325eddb523f6449ba06a2deb0885a8a7009d
(cherry picked from commit d8307005bfac7d680bb1975733928e52e9053b77)

Run sudo /w -H in akanda post_test_hook

commit_message:
Fix manual assignment of nodes to node groups

Assigning nodes to a node group now works by updating
the 'group_id' attribute on a collection of nodes.

Change-Id: I10ba150ede24a47b75c2ff4dc5bff7c0317e7c22
Closes-bug: #1464682

[WIP] Basic Address Scope neutron client changes

Mainly for backup purposes, don't spend your time reviewing it.
Changes done: Enable creating, reading and deleting address scopes
via REST API. Includes required changes to REST, model.
Work InProgress: REST updation, alembic migrations, and unit tests.

[{'created': '2015-06-22 10:08:42.000000000', 'message': 'Update milestone.sh to support new versioning

Update milestone.sh for liberty-style development milestone releases:
- Derive version from checked-out setup.cfg
- Use common functions for titles and temp space setup
- Remove Swift-specific IS_RELEASE=1 case (as this script is only for
  milestone-driven projects)
- Remove tarball comparison step and HEADSHA warnings (since post-merge
  jobs are so slow we almost never have a good tarball to compare from)

Change-Id: I53ff60097e0a437f7bb02746e10ee70d26d305de
'}]
commit_message:
Update milestone.sh to support new versioning

Update milestone.sh for liberty-style development milestone releases:
- Derive version from checked-out setup.cfg
- Use common functions for titles and temp space setup
- Remove Swift-specific IS_RELEASE=1 case (as this script is only for
  milestone-driven projects)
- Remove tarball comparison step and HEADSHA warnings (since post-merge
  jobs are so slow we almost never have a good tarball to compare from)

commit_message:
Support string flavor IDs

This allows operating on Nova flavors with non-integer ids
by adding a new str_id field to the view that always contains the
unicode flavor id.  The current id field will now contain a value
only when the flavor's id can be cast to int, otherwise it will be
None.  Validation of flavor id when querying a flavor or creating an
instance has been updated to include non-empty strings in addition to
integers.

This will require a patch to python-troveclient to properly fallback
to str_id in absence of the integer id:

    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123301/

(cherry picked from commit 21fee8c3c554ba158c2bbe977131522a204c22cc)

Change-Id: Ie9cfefc6127bc76783cdf9668636342d7590b308
Closes-bug: #1333852

commit_message:
Allow Merge Commits to fuel-docs repo

We need to be able to merge changes to stable branche in bulks for
fuel-docs/

Change-Id: Id21f4987f95444e69275a8b2dbd7cce8a56d8c53
Related-Bug: #1467657

commit_message:
Check both master and env repos for packages

In tests with Ubuntu for environment operation
system some packages on master node (CentOS)
could be updated, so tests must search packages
in both repositories types.

Also copy master node packages to 'deb' section,
because they are needed to determine package
installation target.

Change-Id: I96edc27278229d525da20c9b1237ebded34acaf7
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

[VB guide] Edits

1. Removes 'IMG' from the instructions
2. Changes vboxnet1 IP address to 172.16.0.254
3. Replaces screens
4. Changes adapter type to Intel PRO/1000 MT Desktop

commit_message:
Save custom repository config to separate file

On Ubuntu it's necessary to create separate files
for custom repositories configurations, because
file '/etc/apt/sources.list' is truncated by
'upload_core_repos' deployment task.

Change-Id: I2e1b6294e3fb8704961794fc0bdf9a755a59e837
Closes-bug: #1466756

commit_message:
Check both master and env repos for packages

In tests with Ubuntu for environment operation
system some packages on master node (CentOS)
could be updated, so tests must search packages
in both repositories types.

Also copy master node packages to 'deb' section,
because they are needed to determine package
installation target.

Change-Id: I96edc27278229d525da20c9b1237ebded34acaf7
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-07 13:06:56.000000000', 'message': "Report host memory b/w as a metric in Nova

This spec proposes to introduce host memory b/w as a host metric.
Memory b/w can be a essential piece in determining VM performance
bottlenecks and further can be used for better NUMA based placements.

Using the linux perf APIs, nova-compute should be able to expose
Host's memory bandwidth utilization on every NUMA node.
This memory b/w can be leveraged in Openstack by exposing it as a
monitor.

Change-Id: I26b0766f234f38d54efa3a5f101dca2959621419
Blueprint: memory-bw
"}, {'created': '2015-05-07 18:54:20.000000000', 'message': "Report host memory bandwidth as a metric in Nova

commit_message:
Report host memory bandwidth as a metric in Nova

This spec proposes to introduce host memory bandwidth as a host metric.
Memory bandwidth can be a essential piece in determining VM performance
bottlenecks and further can be used for better NUMA based placements.

Using the linux platform interfaces like perf APIs, nova-compute
should be able to expose Host's memory bandwidth utilization on every
NUMA node.This memory b/w can be leveraged in Openstack by exposing
it as a monitor.

Change-Id: I26b0766f234f38d54efa3a5f101dca2959621419
Blueprint: memory-bw

commit_message:
Keystone get_entities scenario backwards compat

This lets the user supply a service name to the Keystone get_entities
scenario in order to fetch a service other than 'keystone,' which
makes that scenario work for older OpenStack. The user can also supply
None, which will cause the scenario to create a new service, just like
it does for tenant, role, and user.

As a side-effect, this fixes the unit test for get_entities.

Change-Id: I3393c9bdbbab37b6d37c24b0bd7701c0dbbbfe75

commit_message:
Adds Hyper-V Cluster spec

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/hyper-v-cluster

Hyper-V Clustering has been introduced since Windows /
Hyper-V Server 2008
and it introduced several benefits such as highly available VMs,
better performance, faster live migrations and other features.

Currently, there is no support for Hyper-V Clusters in Openstack. This
blueprint is addressing this issue and adds an implementation.

Change-Id: I94b08bba6f1f05c319a183f7fda04ab7122a0ac4
Implements: blueprint hyper-v-cluster

commit_message:
Inject NMI to an instance

This spec adds a new API which injects an NMI (Non-maskable Interruption) to
an instance for triggering a special funciton such as the kernel crash dump
mechanism.

APIImpact

Change-Id: Ibdfc62f085dacf538c3f421598c77f9d57fa3064
Implements: blueprint inject-nmi

commit_message:
rbd: add volume_id to connection_info in initialize_connection

Most other volume drivers have a 'volume_id' key in the
connection_info['data'] dict returned from initialize_connection, this
adds it to the rbd volume driver.

This is part of a bigger effort to standardize the connection_info dict
so that consumers like Nova can rely on a common set of keys when
processing connection_info.

Change-Id: I7aed56a93c4cc3be5e0e49da6ddc1f009fed3c18

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I73addc2c144c76c60f046e83c97e3b6ffe09d879

commit_message:
Ensure lock(s) acquire/release returns boolean values

Some of the returns were missing, so to ensure that the
interface is consistent ensure that we always return true
or false as needed, and add tests to ensure this keeps on
being maintained.

Change-Id: I877111c3a1d1d300881625c5900d4a825c5f1684

commit_message:
Disable SSL v2 and v3

This patch makes SSL v2 and v3 disabled.
SSL v2 and v3 should be deprecated for security reasons.

Change-Id: I3c4c0299eeade7478873f88ac7047d4710cceb52
Closes-Bug: #1348372

commit_message:
Remove graduated oslo.service code

This patch deletes all code that has moved to oslo.service
and updates the MAINTAINERS file accordingly.
Also removed eventlet from requirements as it is no longer used
anywhere.

bp graduate-oslo-service

Change-Id: I61ee911a4bf2f0723a22473edffc4fa2f88b87a4

[{'created': '2015-04-27 17:09:51.000000000', 'message': 'Fix FloatingIP Namespace creation in DVR for Late Binding

DVR has dependency on the porbinding host to determine
where to start the FloatingIP Namespace when floatingip
is configured. But when we assign a floatingip to a port
that is not bound, even though the API will succeed, the
FloatingIP Namespace will not be created by the Agent and
so the FloatingIP will not be functional.

This patch addresses the issue by creating the Namespace
and configuring the rules when the late binding happens.

The agent will be requesting the FIP agent gateway port,
if required and then proceed to configure the FloatingIP
Namespace.

Change-Id: Ifa92f2b09310763262f75b0006333da7a54a6f23
Closes-Bug: #1447034
'}]
commit_message:
Fix FloatingIP Namespace creation in DVR for Late Binding

DVR has dependency on the porbinding host to determine
where to start the FloatingIP Namespace when floatingip
is configured. But when we assign a floatingip to a port
that is not bound, even though the API will succeed, the
FloatingIP Namespace will not be created by the Agent and
so the FloatingIP will not be functional.

This patch addresses the issue by creating the Namespace
and configuring the rules when the late binding happens.

The agent will be requesting the FIP agent gateway port,
if required and then proceed to configure the FloatingIP
Namespace.

Change-Id: Ifa92f2b09310763262f75b0006333da7a54a6f23
Closes-Bug: #1447034

commit_message:
WIP client use api registration and backup

the freezer client interacts with the api
backup metadata information is sent upon succesful
bakup action has completed

excplicit registration of the client is supported as
an additional admin action

Add the following parameters:

 --action admin --register

Change-Id: Iab0736ee91c9727de5bf5ceb286e5ce8063e4114

Add explicit decoding to asn1 data

Not all data returned from openssl was explicitly decoded. It's a nice
check for python2 and requirement for python3.

commit_message:
Decompose _create_subnet_from_pool

Moved validations into separate methods:
- _validate_pools_with_subnetpool
Verifies that allocation pools are set only for specific subnet request.
For any subnet request allocation pools can not be set manually
- _validate_ip_version_with_subnetpool
Verifies that subnet has the same ip version as subnet pool

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: I63f6aa2a0c94c3437fa624ac800943976f4fc50f

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

Fix sqlite file permission for system-wide install

For system-wide install with sqlite DB, allow write permission to
group and others.

(1 comment)

I think I object to the name of this spec. This is really just an extension of the request-spec-object spec, right? It's just to persist it until the scheduler makes the placement decision, right?

What I mean is, this really should be about:

"Change the API to not immediately create instance entries in the database, persist the request spec, and answer GET requests for an uncreated instance from the request-spec instead of the instance record"

Right?

I think refocusing it in that direction makes it a little clearer what we need to do. Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-04-17 17:53:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Dan, I agree with your restatement.  This was just split out of the dependent spec which I believe was written before the request-spec spec was written.  At this point it is something that should be about presentation of the request-spec in the API during an instance list/show.  I will need to ensure that the request-spec contains everything we need to return for the API and if not we need to find the proper place for it.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-04-20 19:05:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yeah, agreed. We should make this particular part squarely in the way of the API, request-spec, etc and not make it a thing about cells specifically. I think we'll get it spread around more that way too :)"}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2015-04-21 11:55:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add BuildRequest object

In order to always have some persistent data for an instance the
relevant details of the API boot request should be stored before
returning a response.

blueprint add-buildrequest-obj

Change-Id: Iecd46e6d0198fb6cadc140fd7408b2fbf6d94746

commit_message:
Allow non-admin to list all tenants based on policy

Currently, running 'nova list --all-tenants' with a policy change:
"compute:get_all_tenants": "role:special_role or is_admin:True"

will not work as expected, The returned list of servers will not
contain all instances of all tenants. We should support administrators
who wish to enable this functionality in their policy.json.

We need to fix this problem both in the v2 API and in the v2.1 as well.

Deep in instance_get_all_by_filters_sort, there is a check which adds
a filter of project_id or user_id if the context is NOT an admin context.
So, the returned list will be a subset of all the instances in the
database. To fix this scenario, the easy way is to call get_all with
an elevated context to pass this check in instance_get_all_by_filters_sort.

So in fixing the bug above, we need to fix the default policy so that
all-tenants is available by default only to administrators.

UpgradeImpact
SecurityImpact
DocImpact: --all-tenants will list all servers for non-admin
APIImpact: --all-tenants will list all servers for non-admin

Closes-Bug: #1464381
Change-Id: I6fe512ff00a0fde1c75d49efe8bfa5f3d2d34df6

commit_message:
Set conflicts setting for nodes with base-os role

  Since base-os role assigned cannot be combined with other roles, set
  'conflicts' setting to all the roles except itself.

Change-Id: I847bf47365cea5142f22ccd4bcd74624b6ec1c42
Partial-Bug: #1466878

For sake of future python3 encode FakeMemcache hashes

yet run under Python3.

commit_message:
Save custom repository config to separate file

On Ubuntu it's necessary to create separate files
for custom repositories configurations, because
file '/etc/apt/sources.list' is truncated by
'upload_core_repos' deployment task.

Change-Id: I2e1b6294e3fb8704961794fc0bdf9a755a59e837
Closes-bug: #1466756

commit_message:
Add missing Jinja2 to requirements.txt

Recently merged commit I5bbdc0f97db9b0ebd7b48e50ab7869e2ca33aead got in
a dependency on Jinja2 library without adding it to requirements.txt.
The gate was running fine, because Nova already has it in it's
requirements. Problem uncovers when we install DevStack with
--use-venv=True option.

Change-Id: If053c4724d9d0264e0f3b27a995a2b619cf6f515
Closes-Bug: 1466361

commit_message:
Leave control of Redis balancing in static hieradata

Redis balancing is controlled by static hieradata [1] we don't
need to override it into manifest.

1. https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/blob/master/puppet/hieradata/controller.yaml#L111

Change-Id: Ie2a5a4cbee0a55f2572f182b18c036efc299dbef

ProfileInUse exception which is thrown in DB layer, should be
considered as an internal exception. Change ProfileInUse to a
generic ResourceBusyError exception and catch it in api layer
and raise a user facing exception ResourceInUser.

'}]
commit_message:
Change ProfileInUse exception to ResourceBusyError

ProfileInUse exception which is thrown in DB layer, should be
considered as an internal exception. Change ProfileInUse to a
generic ResourceBusyError exception and catch it in api layer
and raise a user facing exception ResourceInUser.
This patch also fixes some error messages.

Partially implements blueprint senlin-exception-handling

Change-Id: I177bdbd4766e9691700e872e81ed02e304b0a2da

commit_message:
MOS-RN6.1 Heat/Murano issues and others.rst edit

This patch:

- adds a known Heat issue: Heat operation failed after controller
  failover;
- adds a new Deployment known issue: Murano deployment failed
  (sometimes?): 0.0.0.0:55572 address already in use;
- moves all release notes from the Issues in OpenStack Components
  to their appropriate sections.

Change-Id: I183477dc285fc1327dffa4c9999db17425ca4d7d
Co-Authored-By: Maria Zlatkova <mzlatkova@mirantis.com>
Closes-Bug: #1467488

commit_message:
Switch to use oslo.service

The 'oslo.service' has graduated now. We should switch to use it from
now on. Maintaining a copy of code we don't own is not fun.

Change-Id: I92372ae64ea6bb0a456b88218c1de91605377a19

Avoid using 'type' keyword as variable name

As a general guideline, we should avoid using reserved keywords as the
names of variables.

commit_message:
Add CDH5.4 support in sahara

We add a directory v_5_4_0 in cdh plugin, so that we have a
choice 5.4.0 when cdh plugin is chosen.

Implements: blueprint cdh-5-4-support
Change-Id: I05d2082b589eb031b0ce1b5a253dc62a75912e1b

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-15 12:13:58.000000000', 'message': "API: Get a subset of fields from Nodes

Sometimes we don't care about all fields in a node (or a collection
of them) and only need a particular subset of fields for a particular
operation. This can save a lot of bandwidth depending on the information
contained in the nodes, for example, a node which contains a config drive
bsae64 enconded in it's instance_info field can be pretty heavy (a
collection of them ...)

This patch allows users to specify a list of fields that will be returned
when GET'ing a node or a collection of nodes.

E.g

GET v1/nodes/<uuid>?fields=uuid,provision_state,power_state

GET v1/nodes?fields=uuid,provision_state,power_state

GET v1/nodes?fields=uuid,provision_state,power_state&instance_uuid=<instance uuid>

Change-Id: Iee3b8821afeb670848d4030a5d1a29b356bb5559

commit_message:
API: Get a subset of fields from Nodes

Sometimes we don't care about all fields in a node (or a collection
of them) and only need a particular subset of fields for a particular
operation. This can save a lot of bandwidth depending on the information
contained in the nodes, for example, a node which contains a config drive
bsae64 encoded in it's instance_info field can be pretty heavy (a
collection of them ...)

This patch allows users to specify a list of fields that will be returned
when GET'ing a node or a collection of nodes.

E.g

Get the uuid, provision_state and power_state of a particular node:

  GET v1/nodes/<uuid>?fields=uuid,provision_state,power_state

Get the uuid, provision_state and power_state of a collection of nodes:

  GET v1/nodes?fields=uuid,provision_state,power_state

Get the uuid, provision_state and power_state of a particular node associated
with a particular instance:

  GET v1/nodes?fields=uuid,provision_state,power_state&instance_uuid=<instance uuid>

Since we are introducing a new feature in the API this patch bumps the
micro version to 1.8

APIImpact
Partial-Bug: #1466495
Related-Bug: #1458934
Change-Id: Iee3b8821afeb670848d4030a5d1a29b356bb5559

commit_message:
Allowing data souce objects to be updated

Data Source objects can now be updated as long as they
are not referenced by an active job in the PENDING state.

Change-Id: I1d29ed73e635c1314cdd01fdbd6dd84645cabec5
Partial-Implements: bp edp-edit-data-sources

commit_message:
Add support for isolating block storage nets

This patch updates the cinder block storage role
for Puppet so that it supports network isolation.
This includes using the (optional) isolated networks
for MySQL, Glance API, and iscsi network traffic.

Change-Id: Icdfbf5fce7380e6049babca0cd50ca2e4008c1b0

commit_message:
Use the same snapshot name if none provided

If snapshot name was not provided when calling 'dos.py snapshot env-name',
a timestamp was used, but it was calculated for each node separately which
caused different names for different nodes.
This fix use timestamp that was generated for all nodes.

Change-Id: I7ef80f4b748d8c0d2ca8297758c32f3bf2e866d7
Closes-Bug: #1456116

commit_message:
Add creation date column to snapshot list

* Added wrapper around snapshots returned by libvirt to make whole code
  more pythonic
* Snapshots are sorted by creation date by default
* Added lxml as runtime dependency
* Added tabulate as runtime dependency and used to print snapshot
  tabular data

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1463361

Change-Id: Ia2c2fab4ac763865ab3f837c63a87101e567d6e8

commit_message:
Improved testing of Volume XML building

Added factories for Volume and Environment and used in test
Increased py.test verbosity (for diffs in asserts)
More and better test cases for Volume XML

Partial-Bug: #1462906

commit_message:
CI TEST

This will allow a basic all in one environment test to be run against
the openstack cookbook repo.  Once in place, it can also then be used
by individual cookbook patches to run the same tests.  This is just a
starting point for our CI work, see the todo list below.

- setup for using new experiemental gate
- run aio neutron environment
- run tests
- check for idempotency

TODOs
- get basic networking (local or flat) working on one nic
- gather logging info for failures (infra publish gate change?)
- multinode environment

Change-Id: I23ebc6092fc563ebfa0a9882668a5f51937a3013

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-15 13:36:26.000000000', 'message': 'Fix l3 agent to not create already deleted router

In case router is deleted during l3 agent resync,
the "deleted" event is processed with higher priority, then
resync event for the router may be processed which will recreate
already deleted router.
The fix adds "deleted" event with lower priority as well which
eliminates the chance of router recreation by resync task.

Logging was improved to make debugging a bit easier.

Closes-Bug: #1455439
Change-Id: I2d060064acccc10591a3d90be9011f116548cfce
'}, {'created': '2015-05-27 15:15:19.000000000', 'message': 'Fix l3 agent to not create already deleted router

In case router is deleted during l3 agent resync,
the "deleted" event is processed with higher priority, then
resync event for the router may be processed which will recreate
already deleted router.
This happens due to timestamp not being properly updated for deleted
router in router processor.
The fix adds timestamp update for deleted router.

Functional tests were updated and now handle 3 cases for l3 sync:
 - no routers were deleted during agent downtime,
 - some routers were deleted during agent downtime
 - some routers were deleted during agent resync

Logging was improved to make debugging a bit easier.

Closes-Bug: #1455439
Change-Id: I2d060064acccc10591a3d90be9011f116548cfce

commit_message:
Fix l3 agent to not create already deleted router

In case router is deleted during l3 agent resync,
the "deleted" event is processed with higher priority, then
resync event for the router may be processed which will recreate
already deleted router.
This happens due to timestamp not being properly updated for deleted
router in router processor.
The fix adds timestamp update for deleted router.

Functional test will be updated in a follow-up patch

Logging was improved to make debugging a bit easier.

Closes-Bug: #1455439
Change-Id: I2d060064acccc10591a3d90be9011f116548cfce

commit_message:
Add testing using py.test

* added py27 tox env to default env list
* added pytest and pytest-django as test requirements
* tests with database marked as expected to fail until DB will
  be configured correctly on CI
* fixed issues and fails in tests

Partial-Bug: #1462906
Change-Id: I4e37ca12c645950eedc9ced5b59daf1fd22005ee

commit_message:
Drop suds dependency

suds has been replaced with suds-jurko in:

* oslo.vmware: I699c65e4abd607ea6f377d86c45fd609569f3c2b
* cinder: I646602624af7fbece277fe2305a3a541a456ed85
* nova: I28f29d3e5745c21b99dc0cf9eb0cfe4f95dffd17

suds-jurko is maintained and compatible with Python 3, whereas suds is
no more maintained.

suds is no more used in OpenStack, it can be dropped.

Change-Id: I4fc2a32ec634b7b4a7ec54144828782ed4ddcb52

commit_message:
More info on how to create ec2 credential

The help message on how to create ec2 type V3 credential is not
clear enough, we need more info when using OpenStack CLI to create
ec2 type V3 credential.

Change-Id: I99b28b13d9d1e94bbaebaba4a2a9f7ec9f646d38
Co-Authored-By: Zhenzan Zhou <zhenzan.zhou@intel.com>
Closes-Bug: #1464874

commit_message:
Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL

As discussed in the Liberty Design Summit "Moving apps to Python 3"
cross-project workshop, the way forward in the near future is to
switch to the pure-python PyMySQL library as a default.

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-cross-project-python3

Also set the OS_TEST_DBAPI_ADMIN_CONNECTION override variable so
that oslo.db opportunistic detection will know to use PyMySQL until
I12b32dc097a121bd43991bc38dd4d289b65e86c1 makes it the default
behavior.

Change-Id: Icd91a065d3c4f62791ba0dca99a822e3a1a0ad44
Co-Authored-By: Victor Sergeyev <vsergeyev@mirantis.com>

[{'created': '2015-06-18 20:34:57.000000000', 'message': 'Get better at closing WSGI iterables.

PEP 333 (WSGI) says: "If the iterable returned by the application has
a close() method, the server or gateway must call that method upon
completion of the current request[.]"

There's a bunch of places where we weren't doing that; some of them
matter more than others. Calling .close() can prevent a connection
leak in some cases. In others, it just provides a certain pedantic
smugness. Either way, we should do what WSGI requires.

Noteworthy goofs include:

  * If a client is downloading a large object and disconnects halfway
    through, a proxy -> obj connection may be leaked. In this case,
    the WSGI iterable is a SegmentedIterable, which lacked a close()
    method. Thus, when the WSGI server noticed the client disconnect,
    it had no way of telling the SegmentedIterable about it, and so
    the underlying iterable for the segment's data didn't get
    closed.

    Here, it seems likely (though unproven) that the object server
    would time out and kill the connection, or that a
    ChunkWriteTimeout would fire down in the proxy server, so the
    leaked connection would eventually go away. However, a flurry of
    client disconnects could leave a big pile of useless connections.

  * If a conditional request receives a 304 or 412, the underlying
    app_iter is not closed. This mostly affects conditional requests
    for large objects.

The leaked connections were noticed by this patch's co-author, who
made the changes to SegmentedIterable. Those changes helped, but did
not completely fix, the issue. The rest of the patch is an attempt to
plug the rest of the holes.

Co-Authored-By: Romain LE DISEZ<romain.ledisez@ovh.net>

Change-Id: I168e147aae7c1728e7e3fdabb7fba6f2d747d937
Closes-Bug: #1466549

commit_message:
Get better at closing WSGI iterables.

PEP 333 (WSGI) says: "If the iterable returned by the application has
a close() method, the server or gateway must call that method upon
completion of the current request[.]"

There's a bunch of places where we weren't doing that; some of them
matter more than others. Calling .close() can prevent a connection
leak in some cases. In others, it just provides a certain pedantic
smugness. Either way, we should do what WSGI requires.

Noteworthy goofs include:

  * If a client is downloading a large object and disconnects halfway
    through, a proxy -> obj connection may be leaked. In this case,
    the WSGI iterable is a SegmentedIterable, which lacked a close()
    method. Thus, when the WSGI server noticed the client disconnect,
    it had no way of telling the SegmentedIterable about it, and so
    the underlying iterable for the segment's data didn't get
    closed.

    Here, it seems likely (though unproven) that the object server
    would time out and kill the connection, or that a
    ChunkWriteTimeout would fire down in the proxy server, so the
    leaked connection would eventually go away. However, a flurry of
    client disconnects could leave a big pile of useless connections.

  * If a conditional request receives a 304 or 412, the underlying
    app_iter is not closed. This mostly affects conditional requests
    for large objects.

The leaked connections were noticed by this patch's co-author, who
made the changes to SegmentedIterable. Those changes helped, but did
not completely fix, the issue. The rest of the patch is an attempt to
plug the rest of the holes.

Co-Authored-By: Romain LE DISEZ <romain.ledisez@ovh.net>

Change-Id: I168e147aae7c1728e7e3fdabb7fba6f2d747d937
Closes-Bug: #1466549

has updated to use horizon angular dashboard,when this put to stackforge or openstack (needs David Lyle ack first), you can push your codes there, thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2015-06-19 17:48:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Discussion with(in) the Ironic project team about this has only recently started -- we were not aware of this project before it was proposed (along with 2,500 lines of code) to gerrit. This project hasn't been developed "in the open", which is surprising and unfortunate.

If this is to be a Horizon component, and the Horizon team wants to maintain it, or accept Niu as the maintainer of this code within that team, that's great. I probably won't object, but I would prefer it to be within the Ironic team.

That said, I think a more modular approach which provides a UI that can be used both stand-alone and within Horizon -- iow, the approach that Michael is taking, which has been discussed over the past few months with the Ironic project team -- would be much better. It may be some time before Michael's approach is ready, and we can have multiple implementations of a thing within openstack.

In any case, this needs to be done as a collaboration with the community, and the Ironic developer community needs some time to look at and evaluate this project, and decide whether we want to embrace it.

So I am -1'ing for now, until we have had time to review and discuss it more.'}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2015-06-23 08:16:12.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
VMWare NSXv: Add distributed URL locking to ini

NSXv plugin supports distributed locking using tooz library.
This patch adds the required parameter to the ini file.

DocImpact

Depends-On: Icbcec938c1c5ae7a528350f2f283388b81fa66b7
Change-Id: I8a7c36d044c4be29b0dfa3fbb8e9379723cebd61

commit_message:
Decompose create_port and save_subnet

This commit is a preparation step for enabling pluggable ipam.
Some actions in create_port and save_subnet are specific for
non pluggable ipam implementation.

- create_port
Moved allocation ips for port and storing results into separate method
_allocate_ips_for_port_and_store.
Moved to ipam_non_pluggable_backend, since pluggable implementation will
be different due to rollback on failure logic included.

- save_subnet
Moved saving allocation pools into new method _save_allocation_pools.
Moved to ipam_non_pluggable_backend, since pluggable ipam implementation
does not need to save IPAvailabilityRange (availability ranges are
maintained by ipam driver for pluggable case)

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: I4a3e5d7f3aa54630279d9589225a509c96ed2186

commit_message:
Admin state column added in load balancer tables

Admin state column is missing in all the load
balancer tables(pool, member and monitors tables).

This patch is adds the admin state column
in all the load balancer tables with the display
choices to translate the values.

Change-Id: I259fecef98e3dfea974d26c23a3679f094136699
Closes-bug: #1436811

commit_message:
Python3: do not set Request.body to a text string

In Python 3, Request.body must be set to a bytes object.

Change-Id: I17785d1e9eb253a1c6cae300b207fb0a08873b0e
Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
Hide attach fip if already fip attached

Only one floating ip is allowed for one instance.
If we try to attach one more IP we are getting error message.
This patch hiding the attach IP action button,
if the instance is already attached with one FIP

Change-Id: I9be93817183ec0187fc8543a95a3b2cd0709e599

commit_message:
Finish switch to inspector and inspector-client

This change is a bit ahead of time, as inspector was not released yet,
but we have chicken-and-egg problem with fixing inspector devstack here.

Change-Id: Iddb5377450806ad768582a705e1c4274079b002f

commit_message:
Remove v3 from nova code tree

This spec describes the plan of removing any 'v3' stuff from nova
code tree and restructure the nova api code tree.

Related to Bug #1462901

commit_message:
Add option to not run db sync

Database syncs should not be required every time a container starts.
We can default database startup to true, but give the option
to set it to false.

Change-Id: Ib76876b2671f6c31f4511412efd3a438ec78f01f
Closes-bug: #1467576

commit_message:
Add missing documentation for x-fresh-metadata

This patch adds a documentation 'x-fresh-metadata' header for COPY
request. That has been already used but undocumented yet. (Especially
Tempest has already kept the API tests even though undocumented!)

Original discussion came up from here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/178927/

Change-Id: Id6b50e222888da7b8d0920cd2fdbf4a5a77de21e

commit_message:
Change PolicyNotAttached to an internal exception and handle it

Currently PolicyNotAttached is used both cluster_policy.load() and
engine.service, and in the former layer it should be treated as
an internal error.
This patch adds a new PolicyBindingNotFound exception to handle the
internal error, and maps it to HTTPNotFound.

Partially implements blueprint senlin-exception-handling

Change-Id: Iaed43462acfb25e4d74693c420ea193d9c176b8d

commit_message:
Change PolicyInUse exception to ResourceBusyError

Currently PolicyInUse is thrown in DB layer, this
exception should be considered as an internal exception.
Change PolicyInUse to a generic ResourceBusyError exception
and catch it in engine.resource layer and raise a user faced
exception ResourceInUser. Finally mapped ResourceInUser to
HTTPConflict.
This patch also adds a parent class InternalError for all
internal exceptions.

Partially implements blueprint senlin-exception-handling

Change-Id: I1ae9bf1018d41c641719d7e12725e74b7f91cad5

commit_message:
EC Ssync:  Update parms to include node and frag indices

Previously we sent the ssync backend frag index based on the node
index.  We need to be more specific for ssync to handle both sync
and revert cases so now we send the frag index based on the job
contents (as determined by the ec recon)) and the node index
as a new header based on, well, the node index.

The rcvr can now validate the incoming pair to reject (400) when
a primary node is being asked to accept fragments that don't
belong to it.  Additionally, by having the frag index the
rcvr can reject (409) an attempt to accept a fragment when its
a handoff and already has one that needs to be reverted.

Fixes-bug: #1452619
Change-Id: I8287b274bbbd00903c1975fe49375590af697be4

commit_message:
Add option to configure passes in erase_devices

Today, there is no option to configure number of iterations to be
done for shred block device erasing and defaults it to 1. This patch
adds a configuration option to change the number of passes to be done
to erase a block device.

Change-Id: Ia870862f2abe830dee5e19a1c247e3f9399c6db2
Depends-On: I1921d33a6b364c4682b6c9baaf61ac092cfa11d7
Closes-Bug:#1465130

commit_message:
Fix for retrieving alarms

Fixes UnboundLocalVariable for get_data, get_context_data methods.
Removes unnecessary second usage of paginator.page(1) in PageNotAnInteger catch.

Change-Id: Ife868116d1b3bcdc0623e7dd93c7f44a68ab244f

commit_message:
Distributed DHCP Agents

Distributing the DHCP across compute nodes will offer better scalability
and limit the failure domain of the IPAM service.

Change-Id: I508b3aa56bcc6977f36fd8b4c2d372d4849f6588

commit_message:
Use stevedore for auth drivers

The Stevedore library is used for loading auth drivers rather
than using importutils. This provides a level of indirection for
deployers/packagers.

The importutils method of loading drivers is still supported, but
it's deprecated.

bp stevedore

Change-Id: I170a5e422805e988ac472676c8838d8cc7a1ad77

commit_message:
avoid sleep too much when system time changed

We have found that loopingcall will sleep more than specified interval
when system time is changed to elder time (ntp issue), then the loopingcall
thread sleeps too much.

This patch ensures the sleep time not longer than interval.

Change-Id: I0edf0dbb95a7e0d85fd740abc19abb3fd60e90f2

[{'created': '2015-06-19 23:11:15.000000000', 'message': "Wrapping single metrics in a list on post

For efficiency we're using the Kafka clients send_messages function which takes
a variable number of messages to send and batches them so that they can be read
one at a time.  To do this we use the * operator to expand the list of metrics
as we pass them to the send_messages function.  If the input data is not a list
this doesn't work so even single metrics need to be bundled in a list.

Change-Id: I2f196b37db0db95a5163696f14258a865fa9a615
"}]
commit_message:
Wrapping single metrics in a list on post

For efficiency we're using the Kafka clients send_messages function which takes
a variable number of messages to send and batches them so that they can be read
one at a time.  To do this we use the * operator to expand the list of metrics
as we pass them to the send_messages function.  If the input data is not a list
this doesn't work so even single metrics need to be bundled in a list.

Change-Id: I2f196b37db0db95a5163696f14258a865fa9a615

commit_message:
Refactor token fetching

Refactor the code that handles fetching a token either from cache,
decoded from PKI or from keystone. This will allow us to substitute a
new method of fetching a token (like from the keystone database) in
other scenarios.

This change adds a number of tests that have been saved up from recent
reviews as the class now resembles what we would want to subclass from
a service such as keystone. 

Change-Id: I8dc002316404a4bd0e9ea55a727adb2e27ae9a3e

commit_message:
Fix Datera driver export call

A previous commit 3fabed9d64696a204263fd7e00b65115a8ecce87 broke the
export call for the Datera driver. This allows the information to
correctly be accessed again.

Change-Id: I4775700e7a416bf5ebcb5e39f604b270e27f284d
Closes-Bug: #1466967

commit_message:
Handle AttributeError when creating a profile

When creating a profile with a invalid yaml file, AttributeError
will happen, the exception is not handled. This patch fixes this
bug.

Change-Id: I4c08d2e9edf240a5b5e6c9fdc2f666b62a35e722
Closes-bug: #1465154

commit_message:
Fix up some bits of resource_tracker to use instance flavors

This cleans up ResourceTracker and associated tests to use flavors
attached to the instance instead of relying on compatibility
interfaces.

Change-Id: Ibe1448b59ca370b260e8021c449a2c8c8b4f1c17

commit_message:
Rename label of remove router from firewall

The label of remove router from firewall is ambiguous, this patch rename it
to be more distinct, better to understand.

Change-Id: Iea3ab2e4ace75c14bcc3145c02f155136c49ff28
Closes-Bug: #1467208

commit_message:
remove deprecated oslo.utils.timeutils.isotime

oslo.utils.timeutils.isotime is marked as deprecated since version
1.6, this patch removes existent usage and replaces it with recommended
datetime.datetime.isoformat

Change-Id: Ic42bfe38db10a680a5c75d3f21b0069635071f6e

commit_message:
Guru Meditation Reports broken without version_string

The versions from many openstack projects don't provide the
vendor_string,product_string,version_string_with_package.
We need to keep compatible with these projects.

Closes-Bug:#1456465
Change-Id: I688ef29b84541d3261f6b9395b3f591b276aa071
(cherry-picked from oslo-incubator commit
14874b8a836b9580a94a118ed535898cfa76362f)

commit_message:
Fix intermittent test failures because of sort order

Both py27 and py34 jobs fail intermittently and i can
recreate the problem even in my local environment by
repeatedly running "tox -e py27,py34". Fixing up the
sort order helps fix the this issue.

Change-Id: I680c8e986af9177c759740ecb8b94b288386c1bf

commit_message:
Remove deprecated PolicyData class

We are now moving the policy data storage into each action. This class
is useless now. Better remove it to avoid confusion.

Change-Id: I19bf89763dbbe3d26d6dd8afd2cf8f9c2b28aa7d

commit_message:
read_hosts_file_leases shouldn't parse stateless IPv6

Error when _read_hosts_file_leases tries to parse stateless IPv6 entry
in hosts file
TRACE neutron.agent.dhcp.agent ip = host[2].strip('[]')
TRACE neutron.agent.dhcp.agent IndexError: list index out of range

Neutron creates entries in dhcp host file for each subnet of a port.
Each of these entries will have same mac address as first field,
and may have client_id, fqdn, ipv4/ipv6 address for dhcp/dhcpv6 stateful,
or tag as other fields.

For dhcpv6 stateless subnet with extra_dhcp_opts,
host file will have only mac address and tag. So _read_hosts_file_leases
shouldn't check for ip address for this entry in host file.

Closes-bug: #1465330
Change-Id: Iad6605ac5c7bcd6ec9204352037ed021f5007738
