This seems like a sensible way to accomplish one of the things that people think ceilometer does but it doesn't quite: monitoring system events in near real time.

It's sensible because it imagines doing it leveraging the messaging bus and using a new and separate service.

I worry though because of a couple of issues:

* There's been discussion of moving the entire alarm-related subsystem into its own repository and managing it effectively as its own independent set of tools. If that happens, this service would need to fit in with that plan.
* I was going to say something about potential performance issues but we shouldn't worry about that yet, that's premature optimization of an environment we haven't even seen yet."}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-04-14 13:22:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-04-14 14:36:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Hi Ryota,

Thanks for this spec. It looks like a good proposal to cover the currently missing alarming functionality for events, which is important to cover in the upcoming Liberty release. I added some comments inline, please check.

In the sense of talking about real-time and monitoring I agree with Chris. Ceilometer is not intended to be a monitoring tool and in this sense the functionality of it does not cover any real-time requirements in that area. As for this spec, I don't think that it should affect the implementation of alarming functionality on events though.

@Chris: Is there a plan to have a session for these architectural questions like the different repos or do we plan to discuss it prior to the summit?

Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-04-14 15:53:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ildiko:

* I think we need to have both a session at summit and a bit of discussion beforehand (so we can bound the conversations somewhat). I plan to put something on the session spreadsheet soon. Do you think it would be better to do the ground-laying discussion in some strawmen specs or on the mailing list?

* My comment was meant to think that people do think ceilometer is a monitoring tool and this spec will bring it closer to satisfying that use case. Despite our efforts to discourage that perception it is something people want, probably because of the _hugely_ valuable collection of data that ceilometer consumes. What this spec does well is create a clear division between alarms which use events and could be reasonably expected to be thought of as "monitoring" data sources and alarms which use metrics and should really only be used for things like auto scaling and the like.

I think this spec is one of several good concrete starting points for the discussion about the evolution of ceilometer that needs to happen, so very cool to see it in place.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-04-14 17:55:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1894, 'date': '2015-04-15 09:39:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(5 comments)

Thank you for letting me know discussion so far. I'll keep in my mind about "alarm subsystem separation".

I understand some people might not request such real-time feature to Ceilometer, but I believe this feature useful to end users typically who keep sending GET requests to OpenStack services to figure out what happed in cloud. Ceilometer already handling various notification from other OpenStack services and also has a mechanism to send notification to end users, so I proposed to integrate this two functions that provides great value to end users.

I'd like to list discussion points of "Alerting on events" to get high-level consensus and determine ideal approach before having detailed discussion of API, optimization and etc.

1. Alerting in real-time

Can we develop this real-time alerting function in Ceilometer or not?

I think it is one of well-known requests as alerting function which handles simple case like capturing situation that binary value toggled e.g. "instance.active".
In such case, user may want receive notification as soon as possible, tough if there are lots of process running in server side.
Also, this feature should be nice as alerting function which is integrated with Heat.
So, I hope the development of this feature held in Ceilometer.
What do you think?


2. Event Preservation

Do we have to store all events to realize "Alerting on events"?

Storing events and evaluating them from existing alarm evaluator could be another approach, but this will not be reasonable to "alerting on events" since people want immediate notification. This might be a small step to adding new alarm type and new rule for that alarm type into API spec, but we can skip that step and focus on handling events on the fly.


3. Alarms vs Events

How to find situation to alert?

There was assumption that there are bunch of samples continually spawned, so iterating evaluation by alarms is suitable.
For events, we have to consider another situation since events will occurred once in a while.
Triggering alarm evaluation when it received event could be more efficient in this case.


If I miss points that already discussed, please let me know.


Thanks,
Ryota'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-04-15 14:45:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This blueprint proposes to add a new alarm evaluator for handling alarms

commit_message:
Add spec for event alarm evaluator

This blueprint proposes to add a new alarm evaluator for handling alarms
on events passed from other OpenStack services, that provides event-driven
alarm evaluation which makes new sequence in Ceilometer for handling
alarms on events separated from other types of alarms handled in the
existing polling-based Alarm Evaluator, and realizes immediate alarm
notification to end users.

APIImpact
DocImpact

blueprint: event-alarm-evaluator

Change-Id: Ie5ff0698a611eecd3f94a9d369795d685c0247ae

commit_message:
Add RPC command, delete if last FIP on Agent

Today FloatingIP Agent gateway port is deleted and
recreated for DVR based on the private port binding
of the VMs in the compute node.
This introduces lot more strain on the plugin to
create and delete these ports when VMs come up and
get deleted that are associated with FloatingIPs.

This patch will introduce an RPC call for the agent
to initiate a port delete.

Also the agent will look for the last floatingip that
it manages, and if condition satisfies, the agent will
request the server to remove the FloatingIP Agent
Gateway port.

Change-Id: Ie58531c819cba7602ec947be2ce63ed71c5589d7
Related-Bug: #1408855

force setted to 'Launch Instance' in method allowed in class LaunchLink

commit_message:
Add handle for protocol value "any" in CSR1kv driver

The firewall rule dictionary will have {"protocol": None, ...} if
protocol is set to "any" by the user.

Add a handle in CSR1kv driver to properly convert the protocol "any" in
firewall rule into CSR RESTAPI protocol value "all".

Close-Bug: 1463777
Change-Id: I9018f78f6859f8e4fb7d1461097f9f945a9f9727

[{'created': '2015-05-26 10:41:43.000000000', 'message': 'Haproxy socket bind failing for IPv6 vip address

LBaaS is failing to spawn haproxy for ipv6 SLAAC subnet.
Haproxy socket binding to IPv6 VIP address is failing
as the IPv6 address is just created and is a tentative address.
So wait till the tentative flag is cleared and then
let haproxy is allowed to bind socket to this address.

Change-Id: I49a3c5fd4394eced7b67692ce28414a936ea107c
Closes-bug: #1403001
'}]
commit_message:
Haproxy socket bind failing for IPv6 vip address

LBaaS is failing to spawn haproxy for ipv6 SLAAC subnet.
Haproxy socket binding to IPv6 VIP address is failing
as the IPv6 address is just created and is a tentative address.
So wait till the tentative flag is cleared and then
let haproxy is allowed to bind socket to this address.

Change-Id: I49a3c5fd4394eced7b67692ce28414a936ea107c
Closes-bug: #1403001

commit_message:
Fix RPC version to be a string

The RPC version was being passed as a float which caused an
exception.

Change-Id: I2a2888fcafcc426009fc841b81049a22e072ce75
Closes-Bug: #1467087

Add alternative login description in neutronclient docs

A way to test it is to follow the description and create
a neutron client using the alternative way

Make changes based on Akihiro comments
Add extra colon in line 19

The nova server liberty version is changing from 2015.2 to 12.0.0 and
the 2016.1 'M' release will be 13.0.0 so update the deprecation warnings

commit_message:
Change future nova version number references based on new values

The nova server liberty version is changing from 2015.2 to 12.0.0 and
the 2016.1 'M' release will be 13.0.0 so update the deprecation warnings
in the docs and code using those versions.

Depends on nova change 192406.

Change-Id: I6a35fa0dda798fad93b804d00a46af80f08d475c

The change to fake_instance here has a couple impacts in the
vmware driver, the test_server_password, and test_nova_manage
tests.

Add fip to lbaas vip info

This change adds floating ip address where the vip is displayed.  The
floating IP is a critical peice of information and it is a real hassle
to find this information.

Change-Id: Id9cfeffd3eebe7651bc53baa5e52972ce2c50547
Closes-bug: #1452411

Refactor extract function load_auth_method

A load_auth_method function is extracted from load_auth_methods
so that it's easier to modify and unit test.

bp stevedore

[{'created': '2015-06-22 21:14:01.000000000', 'message': 'Cleanup the fip agent gateway port delete routines

Based on the parent patch, right now the Floatingip
agent gateway ports will only be deleted when the
external gateway port associated with the router is
deleted.

The Floatingip agent gateway port will not be deleted
for every association and disassociation.

The Floatingip agent gateway port was created on all
nodes as a substitute for the gateway port. So it makes
sense to delete those ports only when the gateway port
is deleted.

The agent should be able to delete the floatingip agent
gateway port on a given external network when it is not
required.

This would substantially reduce the burden on the server
to validate, read and delete from the DB.

Change-Id: I6721d1f8ecfaa7fbca311c49aaf658c4624cb668
Related-Bug: #1408855
'}]
commit_message:
Cleanup the fip agent gateway port delete routines

Based on the parent patch, right now the Floatingip
agent gateway ports will only be deleted when the
external gateway port associated with the router is
deleted.

The Floatingip agent gateway port will not be deleted
for every association and disassociation.

The Floatingip agent gateway port was created on all
nodes as a substitute for the gateway port. So it makes
sense to delete those ports only when the gateway port
is deleted.

The agent should be able to delete the floatingip agent
gateway port on a given external network when it is not
required.

This would substantially reduce the burden on the server
to validate, read and delete from the DB.

Change-Id: I6721d1f8ecfaa7fbca311c49aaf658c4624cb668
Related-Bug: #1408855

commit_message:
Add lbaasv1 api job to the check queue, non-voting

This is part of removing the lbaas tests from tempest. Run the lbaas v1
tests from the neutron-lbaas repo, alongside the v2 tests, so we can delete
them from the tempest and neutron test runs.

Change-Id: Ic84834e0c69ef8bda72c47d8ba075b18ec871ee4

This edit mostly alters the naming of the app module from "hz.dashboard.app" to "horizon.app". Note that this implies moving it from the dashboard module - which the app lists as a dependency - and also the intent to move all of the code into the "horizon" module space. A subsequent patch will move all other openstack_dashboard "hz." module code to "horizon.".

This edit of the patch introduces something potentially contentious: the removal of hzUtils.log (and hzConfig.debug which was only used by hzUtils.log).

As explained in the commit message, the log function was only used in one place, and keeping it meant doing considerable additional work to resolve the dependency from the framework to the dashboard (horizon.util.tech-debt depending on horizon.app.conf).

Alternatives to this edit are welcome.'}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-05-27 03:33:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-27 04:10:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified-1

commit_message:
ngReorg - move dashboard-app to dashboard

Move the angular app module from the framework to
openstack_dashboard at the top level as "horizon.app".

This edit also removes the old hzUtils.log function: it
exists in the framework, but is configured in the application,
thus causing dependency issues. It is only used in one place
(hz.tables.js), and for debugging. I contend that if debugging
is needed then $log can be asked for as needed.

The hzConfig.debug flag was only used by that one function,
so it is also removed in this edit.

Change-Id: Ie538940cd8d1b0eabe677790bad979cc146bfbd1
Closes-Bug: #1458697
Closes-Bug: #1465885

commit_message:
Introduced tempest API tests for openstack/neutron-lbaas

Added missing/empty/invalid fields testcases for:
  create health monitor
  update health monitor
  delete the file test_health_monitors.py

commit_message:
Remove now obsolete English po files, update run_tests

These English po files are not needed anymore, they are the source files.

Update run_tests.sh to use the .pot files as source for generation of
pseudos.

Update transifex config file so that it references the new pot files.

Depends-On: Ibd7069c68e458d655a879e552f69f7146b47abc9
Change-Id: I6c6989176fd7c969ad6cb4ecb4ff4f5e4641e723

commit_message:
Change redstack to use git_timed

When redstack clones repos or issues other git commands,
it issues the commands directly. This can cause failures (hangs)
if transient network errors occur. Devstack has a
workaround for this issue; it implemented timeout and
retry logic when this occurs. This change causes git
calls in redstack to use the devstack git_timed
function.

To enable, just set the GIT_TIMEOUT env var to something
other than 0. (More information is linked in the bug
report referenced here)

Change-Id: Ia224e79573edef6191e6959c44ff52fc0189b6e6
Closes-bug: 1466847

commit_message:
Add explicit alembic dependency

nova/db/sqlalchemy/migration.py directly imports alembic modules
as pointed out by a recent gate-nova-pip-missing-reqs run. So
we should add an explicit dependency in our requirements.txt

Change-Id: I8fc46ab9c5156207af33a41ee6aea5977b58414c

commit_message:
Delete FIP agent gateway port with external-net-delete

FIP agent gateway ports are associated with external
networks and specific host.

Previously the FIP agent gateway port was deleted for
every floatingip associate and disassociate. This was
causing race conditions in the port delete and also
unnecessary access to the db.

This patch will delete the FIP agent gateway port when
external network associated with the Agent port is
deleted.

Change-Id: I8fffd80bc04e3d46d3da1d194dae2c96b6a8d50f
Related-Bug: #1408855

commit_message:
Add floating-ip-address to floatingip-create

a parameter is added to the API.
this patch adds a parameter that is collesponding to the parameter.

partial blueprint allow-specific-floating-ip-address

Change-Id: I232568db11054b73a9a557cb669e570bcd362d6d

commit_message:
Replace oslo incubator code with oslo_service

This is the last in a series of commits to replace our incubator
code with official oslo packages found on PyPI.

Change-Id: I8d40c855699b34bdb3f4ef0e6afd696705afe10a
Closes-Bug: 1463967

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-22 18:42:50.000000000', 'message': "Declare DirectPublisher exchanges with passive=True

If rabbit dies, the consumer can be disconnected before the publisher
sends, and if the consumer hasn't declared the queue, the publisher's
will send a message to an exchange that's not bound to a queue, and
the message wll be lost.  Setting passive=True will cause the
publisher to fail and retry if the consumer hasn't declared the
receiving queue yet.

Backport request of change: 137569

Change-Id: I9009d12688ee23aaa47c394c08d387a13bb15393
Closes-Bug: #1362863
"}, {'created': '2015-06-22 18:45:37.000000000', 'message': 'Always use a poll timeout in the executor

This change allows to stop the eventlet executor without
using eventlet.kill.
And also, the kombu docs actually recommend that drain_events
by default have a 1 timeout.

Backport request of change: 137569

Co-Authored-by: Joshua Harlow <harlowja@yahoo-inc.com>
Change-Id: I9009d12688ee23aaa47c394c08d387a13bb15393
Closes-Bug: #1362863
'}]
commit_message:
Always use a poll timeout in the executor

This change allows to stop the eventlet executor without
using eventlet.kill.
And also, the kombu docs actually recommend that drain_events
by default have a 1 timeout.

Backport request of change: 137569

Co-Authored-by: Joshua Harlow <harlowja@yahoo-inc.com>
Change-Id: I9009d12688ee23aaa47c394c08d387a13bb15393
Closes-Bug: #1362863

commit_message:
Delete Floatingip agent gateway port through rpc

This patch will allow the agent to notify the
plugin to delete the Floatingip agent gateway
port if it is not required anymore.

At present the plugin tries to delete the Floatingip
agent gateway port when floatingip disassociates,
floatingip deletes or when a port using the Floatingip
is deleted.

This introduces more complexity as well as tries to
query the db frequently.

Change-Id: Iab70b68ba1dd61b04f99ff3b4ed819f43693332d
Related-Bug: #1408855

commit_message:
Report bad package when found

When a non-standard package is found in the requirements list, we had an
error saying that but not saying what the bad package name was.

Change-Id: I860c548dce0c8f988f8fd29cead582bf9b9b6850

commit_message:
More selective logging

Having the SDK configure the root logger is problematic as it
not only enables logging in the SDK but it also enables
logging in the users app and logging in other libs unrelated
to the SDK as an unintented side-effect. We should only log
for the openstack module.

We also want to be more selective about what stream to log
to so we provide the option to log to stdout or stderr.

Change-Id: I82ef867e182ebe4f29e21380268a3691e3b83494

commit_message:
Add initial "Stable branches" chapter

First version of the "Stable branches" chapter, covering:
- Support phases
- Appropriate Fixes
- Proposing Fixes
- Stable maintenance teams
- Review guidelines

Based on https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/StableBranch, so containing
text originally authored by Ihar Hrachyshka, Adam Gandelman and
Alan Pevec.

Change-Id: Ia4858bb3a0ccb05944bcb7ab2f5bb81a2f0c1ca9

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-22 21:28:49.000000000', 'message': 'Add check-tempest-dsvm-cells to experimental queue for devstack-gate

There is a giant regex of excluded tests for the tempest-dsvm-cells job
which we plan on whittling down using tempest config options but we need
a way to test changes to remove regexes.

The plan is to move the regexes to devstack-gate but to test them we
need the check-tempest-dsvm-cells job in the experimental queue for d-g.

Related mailing list thread:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067723.html

Change-Id: Icbeecfde1a25ce7265c3696b96aa260d9e2b580d

commit_message:
Add check-tempest-dsvm-cells to experimental queue for devstack-gate

There is a giant regex of excluded tests for the tempest-dsvm-cells job
which we plan on whittling down using tempest config options but we need
a way to test changes to remove regexes.

The plan is to move the regexes to devstack-gate but to test them we
need the check-tempest-dsvm-cells job in the experimental queue for d-g
since job config changes in project-config are currently not self-testing.

Related mailing list thread:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067723.html

Change-Id: Icbeecfde1a25ce7265c3696b96aa260d9e2b580d

commit_message:
Add senlin and its client to project list

This patch adds stackforge/senlin and stackforge/python-senlinclient to
the list of projects that are willing to synchronize their requirements
with the global repo.

Change-Id: I0f6dfe5e0f2e34a23338e9cfb65455a404fc0399

'}, {'created': '2015-06-05 16:05:05.000000000', 'message': 'Mapping Engine CLI

Implementation of a command line wrapped build on top of mapping engine.
Its main goal is checking effects of input parsed by RuleProcessor with
set of provided mapping rules. User must provide two files: a) rules
file with proper JSON with mapping rules (identical to those uploaded to
the server) b) a file with key-value set of environ-like parameters.

Basic usage:

\# keystone-all mapping_engine --help
\# keystone-all mapping_engine --rules <path> --input <path>

Upon successful execution program outputs to the stdout a JSON structure
with effective objects like user, group_ids and user_names.

Change-Id: Ia4b2e617692ebb42693db6d335985dcb6a0969e1

Implementation of a command line wrapped build on top of mapping engine.
Its main goal is checking effects of input parsed by RuleProcessor with
set of provided mapping rules. User must provide two files: a) rules

commit_message:
Mapping Engine CLI

Implementation of a command line wrapped build on top of mapping engine.
Its main goal is checking effects of input parsed by RuleProcessor with
set of provided mapping rules. User must provide two files: a) rules
file with proper JSON with mapping rules (identical to those uploaded to
the server) b) a file with key-value set of environ-like parameters.

Basic usage:

$ keystone-manage mapping_engine --help
$ keystone-manage mapping_engine --rules <path> --input <path>

Upon successful execution program outputs to the stdout a JSON structure
with effective objects like user, group_ids and user_names.

Implements: bp mapping-engine-tester
Change-Id: Ia4b2e617692ebb42693db6d335985dcb6a0969e1

[{'created': '2015-06-22 14:07:53.000000000', 'message': 'Fill project_id in secrets where needed

This CR introduces a migration script that fills the project_id in the
secrets that have it set to None; Which will be the case in the secrets
created before the project_id column was introduced.

On the other hand, this also makes the project_id column in the secrets

commit_message:
Fill project_id in secrets where needed

This CR introduces a migration script that fills the project_id in the
secrets that have it set to None; Which will be the case in the secrets
created before the project_id column was introduced.

On the other hand, this also makes the project_id column in the secrets
table no longer nullable.

blueprint data-remove-tenant-secret-assoc

Change-Id: Iede2d2fcf6487ec3ef1b8d29a6000e2340d4c828

commit_message:
nova.network.linux_net refactor

The nova.network.linux_net module that is responsible for a number
of networking aspects of Nova is quite large and not very flexible
in terms of code maintainance and portability, so it could have a
refactor.

Blueprint: linux-net-refactor
Change-Id: I3c98445349bc82f63913bff90d2baf868c3f7007

[{'created': '2015-06-17 23:25:55.000000000', 'message': "Remove hacking and hacking-owned dependencies.

hacking and the cluster of tools it brings in are updated by projects
in a lazy fashion. As such, tracking the things that hacking specifies
inside global-requirements doesn't make sense: we can't compile them
into the upper-constraints file, since repositories do not upgrade
their codebases in lockstep. We already have a special case where
hacking is passed through as-is without checking its presence in
global-requirements.txt, so this is a very simple change.

Change-Id: I9f8dc9d44c347bc3dfda92ef1a2cfb20c1fe8f8c

commit_message:
Remove hacking and hacking-owned dependencies.

hacking and the cluster of tools it brings in are updated by projects
in a lazy fashion. As such, tracking the things that hacking specifies
inside global-requirements doesn't make sense: we can't compile them
into the upper-constraints file, since repositories do not upgrade
their codebases in lockstep. We already have a special case where
hacking is passed through as-is without checking its presence in
global-requirements.txt, so this is a very simple change.

Change-Id: I9f8dc9d44c347bc3dfda92ef1a2cfb20c1fe8f8c

commit_message:
Guru Meditation Reports broken without version_string

The versions from many openstack projects don't provide the
vendor_string,product_string,version_string_with_package.
We need to keep compatible with these projects.

ported from oslo-incubator change id:
I688ef29b84541d3261f6b9395b3f591b276aa071

Co-Authored-By: zhangchunlong1@huawei.com <zhangchunlong1@huawei.com>
Change-Id: I1560f0b469decec8aa2b9bf9db789876438242b4

commit_message:
Bump python-troveclient version to 1.0.9

python-troveclient has only had both replication parameters (replica_of
and replica_count) since version 1.0.9.  The Heat OS::Trove::Instance
resource makes use of both replication parameters.

Change-Id: Ie91354b14f08e931b5156169052111b5d6ee3285
Closes-Bug: #1462509

commit_message:
Bump kazoo to greater than or equal to 2.2

Kazoo 2.2 was just released (by me) and it fixes
a bunch of bugs that tooz can benefit from (including
special lock handling logic in tooz that is no longer
needed); so this bumps that version so that tooz and
others can take advantage of those fixes.

Change-Id: I5cf30d2952850de140f4bcc8bb3eac100ee8001e

commit_message:
[Floating IP] Remove port creation on fip creation

NeutronWrapper creates a private port when creating a floating IP.
This is bad because:
1. It doesn't make any sense to attach a fip to a standalone port.
2. The method associate_floating_ip() is always called and associates the fip
with a real server.
3. Rally consumes an extra port/ip from the tenant/network.

Change-Id: I932cdf707f6041df4eef8fcd6074ac069678de7b
Closes-Bug: #1465690

commit_message:
unit-tests: add mock decorators usage test checker

This test ensures that @mock.patch and @mock.patch.object decorator arguments
are named with `mock_' prefix and after the mocked object. E.g.:
@mock.patch("abc")
def test_foobar(self, mock_abc).

Parital-Bug: #1462956
Change-Id: I9eaab17bfc0e8c7b85eb56a51d4bcd5884480f2c

commit_message:
Add unit test to exercise key rotation

This reproduces the issue reported in bug 1465444 when applied directly
to master (and actually fails with max_active_keys=4), but passes when
applied to Lance's patch:

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192782/

Change-Id: I045bc97b047dc18983757db052ad6e5bdad11329
Related-Bug: 1465444

commit_message:
Fix Fernet key rotation

Previously, depending on the size of CONF.fernet_tokens.max_active_keys, keys
would be pruned depending on if excess_keys was a negative slice. This caused
the key repository to never actually reach CONF.fernet_tokens.max_active_keys
in the repository in some cases.

Change-Id: Icf47d6612ef0e98e876334f56c993666df081b50
Closes-Bug: 1465444

commit_message:
Add missing keystone-manage commands to doc

domain_config_upload, fernet_rotate, and fernet_setup are missing
from the online configuration documentation for the keystone-manage
command.

This patch adds them using the descriptions found in the man page.

Change-Id: If916589d2a97614bf252ac12bd013b25acb1aa66
Closes-Bug: #1466957

commit_message:
Translations: Update horizon

Horizon uses pot files now as all other projects, adjust scripts for the
change.

Add new Javascript translation for openstack_dashboard.

Remove now unused function compress_non_en_po_files.

commit_message:
Add support for RabbitMQ connection heartbeat

Kilo oslo.messaging added heartbeating support for RabbitMQ
connections.  This patch adds support for this in Puppet modules
by managing the oslo_messaging_rabbit/heartbeat_timeout_theshold
and oslo_messaging_rabbit/heartbeat_rate settings.

Change-Id: Idd6b489b1e1841fab0ce519e0f31f6374129f157

The octavia project recently moved to openstack/octavia, follow name
change in projects.txt.

commit_message:
New oslo library - oslo.service

In Liberty, the oslo team is introducing a new library. At the moment
we have a test version (0.1.0) to see if the API looks good. We would
like projects to try it out. So let's please add it to global requirements.

Change-Id: I305cf53bad6213c151395e93d656b53a8a28e1db

commit_message:
API: Proper error reporting on invalid JSON input

The API framework now explicitly checks for properly formatted JSON
input and no longer relies on the default exception handler for
improperly formed input:

- Added _parse_json_body helper for API handlers
  - Since all calls currently require JSON, this is currently used
    by all handlers.
- Added validation for content-type and charset headers: currently
  only application/json and UTF-8 are accepted.
- Added corresponding unit tests.

Change-Id: Ia7f30cb104e017ac5583fc98f08dccdb34c5a71b
Closes-Bug: #1367888

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 1.12.0

This release has an issue which breaks Ironic, so avoid using it now
that 1.13.0 is available.

Related-Bug: #1461182
Change-Id: I83ea87341258122280dac7fbb4913b015214dff9

commit_message:
Fix the empty string issue for pip

When read from requirement file, the grep not deal with
blank line, which cause pip wheel have '' issue.

Check logs in below for details:
http://logs.openstack.org/21/181821/1/check/check-requirements-integration-dsvm/3ce99ff/console.html#_2015-05-13_05_27_33_105

Change-Id: I558a9488f576738a44dd746589c04bd28d7cd332

[{'created': '2015-05-11 09:04:14.000000000', 'message': 'Bump eventlet version to 0.17.4

Eventlet 0.17.2 and 0.17.3 have the following issue:

 https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/issues/226

which causes requests to fail when using https with a more recent
version of python (>= 2.7.8).

Change-Id: I04cfafb56b5813fddf628abd95a2655acf5e9dd0
'}]
commit_message:
Bump eventlet version to 0.17.4

Eventlet 0.17.2 and 0.17.3 have the following issue:

 https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/issues/226

which causes requests to fail when using https with a more recent
version of python (>= 2.7.8).

Change-Id: I04cfafb56b5813fddf628abd95a2655acf5e9dd0

commit_message:
tests: don't hardcode strace usage

The wait_for_servers helper in glance.tests.functional.FunctionTest
uses the strace(1). While strace(1) is available on FreeBSD, but with a
huge limitation that it works only on i386 hosts.

Instead of always using strace(1), use it only on Linux, for FreeBSD use
the truss(1) tool, that is a native tracing tool that is a part of base
system, and in all other cases just don't try to obtain a trace.

Closes-bug: #1467110
Change-Id: I51cc43fe4ce71eed80bbf4f18f5b060b09494458

commit_message:
Use *.pot files for source language

All other OpenStack projects use *.pot files for the source language.
In the OpenStack CI scripts, we need to special case horizon since
it uses */locale/en/LC_MESSAGES/*po instead. Remove the special handling
from the horizon scripts so that we can simplify the CI scripts.

Note that this simplifies also the run_tests.sh script.

Add empty files for the pot files so that the infra scripts will work.
The next import from the Proposol Bot will add real content for these
files.

Change-Id: I2ae68207994ba549b5d8e551a40a468d63e0a4bb

So the decision to split horizon into horizon and openstack_dashboard was made a while back. This is the primary reason for having two separation folders and hence, two directories for translation.

Doug is also right that we need two translation file, one for client-side and one for server-side. The django.po and djangojs.po is still need to get generated independently via the run_tests.sh script.

I think merging them into one translation file/directory would not require much more work than having a separate script for horizon.'}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-06-11 00:46:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 12071, 'date': '2015-06-11 00:47:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-11 01:31:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

  Use babel to generate message catalogs

Replace django's makemessages with babel and babel-django.

This adds new commands to run_tests

run_tests --makemessages-babel
  Use babel to generate message catalogs

run_tests --compilemessages-babel
  Use babel to complile message catalogs.

Once this patch lands the next step is to write an extractor that
will work with angular-gettext.  That looks mostly straightforward
(with a few wrinkles to work out).

Known Problems

compilemessages-babel fails on the 'mai' locale, which seems to
indicate that babel does not have support for the Maithili
language. A quick look for similar problems suggests that babel
supports locales that are in turn supported by
http://cldr.unicode.org/

Generating the list of locales for each domain is a bit hacky.
Django's compilemessages seems to autodiscover locales, but
pybabel expects the locale(s) to be specified.

Error handling in the compilemessages command needs improvement

Change-Id: If4352aba01ce0ca6337f590c0689d8fe9f0867c8

commit_message:
Replace makemessages with babel

Replace django's makemessages with babel and babel-django.

This changes the makemessages command to use babel rather than
Django's builtin makemessages.

There is a follow on patch to add support for angular-gettext.

Change-Id: If4352aba01ce0ca6337f590c0689d8fe9f0867c8
Depends-On: Iaa835b03af3929b7314b174210079c34de976755

commit_message:
add --slowest flag to testr

with --slowest flag, the slowest unit test cases will be printed,
which is useful to check performance issue.

So this might look a little ugly. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/189250/ was breaking without this.

We can unwind this and discard it once we have constraints in place, but we can't get there without the requirements changes landing, which requires a modern pbr consistently available. Fixing all the deps will be done, but just *one* can break us again, even if its not one of our trees, so I think this is an essential belts-and-braces for the interim."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-06-22 08:34:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2015-06-22 14:42:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-06-22 18:47:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I really feel like this is hitting things with a giant sledge hammer that is going to be hard to unwind, because the work around won't be able to be removed until a bunch of other things happen.

The right fix here is to get those other things happening first. It slows down the requirements work, but it doesn't put a kludge in that can't easily be removed later, and causes masking of real issues.

Having run into a patch that was rushed in for just such a kludge today that's masking real issues (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/194192/) I don't want to do any more of this."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-06-22 19:28:53.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Workaround the headache of pbr downgrades.

We have packages out there that have versioned dependencies on pbr
still and this leads to downgrades when they are installed. Before
we can use recent synced requirements we need a currently valid pbr
version.

Change-Id: Ia8b50d403ecfc57c8f6330cc3f8c0b04b36d4fa2

commit_message:
puppet-gnocchi: enable beaker jobs

Until now, we don't test puppet-gnocchi module with Beaker.
Since we now have packages for CentOS7[1], we might want to start bring
some tests in the module.

[1] http://mirror.centos.org/centos/7/cloud/x86_64/openstack-kilo/

Change-Id: I362cdfc59a082aab1bb016255ebd952a34913b7b

Move Designate-Sink start.sh to docker/common

All start.sh scripts should be in docker/common directory
instead of docker/centos.

Change-Id: Ifc1d07246e3b56156a1dc861e2b262f75c1cd918
